tus), a desktop (where data and applications can be placed), a set of standard desktop tools and applications, and a set of conventions that make it easy for applications to cooperate and be consistent with each other. Users of other operating systems or environments should feel right at home using the powerful graphics-driven environment GNOME provides. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  GNOME is completely open source (free software), with freely available source code developed by hundreds of programmers around the world. If you would like to learn more about the GNOME project please visit the GNOME web site at http://www.gnome.org. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  GNOME has a number of advantages for users. GNOME makes it easy to use and configure applications without using text-only interfaces. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  GNOME is highly configurable, enabling you to set your desktop the way you want it to look and feel. GNOME's session manager remembers previous settings, so once you've set things the way you like they'll stay that way. GNOME supports many human languages, and you can add more without changing the software. GNOME even supports several Drag and Drop protocols for maximum interoperability with applications that aren't GNOME-compliant. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  GNOME also has a number of advantages for developers, which indirectly also help users. Developers don't need to purchase an expensive software license to make their commercial application GNOME compliant. In fact, GNOME is vendor neutral - no component of the interface is controlled solely by one company or restricted from modification and redistribution. GNOME applications can be developed in a variety of computer languages, so you're not stuck with a single language. GNOME uses the Common Object Request Broker Architecture (CORBA) to allow software components to inter-operate seamlessly, regardless of the computer language in which they are implemented, or even what machine they are running on. Finally, GNOME runs on a number of Unix-like operating systems, including Linux. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  GNOME is an acronym for the GNU Network Object Model Environment, so GNOME is a part of the larger GNU project. The GNU Project started in 1984 to develop a completely free Unix-like operating system. If you'd like to learn more about the GNU project you can read about it at http://www.gnu.org. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_ABOUTUG}{\*\bkmkend ID_ABOUTUG}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 1.2. About This Guide\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  This users guide is designed to help you find your way around GNOME with ease. Both new and experienced computer users can benefit from this guide. If you're new to GNOME, or even computers, you'll gain an idea of how to use your desktop. If you're an advanced computer user trying out GNOME, you can work with expert tips, which will help you to become familiar with GNOME. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Although this was written originally in English, there are many translations of the guide available now or in the near future. If you would like to have this guide in another language you should check your operating system distribution or visit the GNOME Web Site (http://www.gnome.org) to find out more information on translation. \hyphpar0\par\sect\sectd\plain\pgwsxn12240\pghsxn15840\marglsxn1440\margrsxn1440\margtsxn1440\margbsxn1920\headery0\footery0\pgndec\titlepg{\headerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}{\headerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i Chapter 2. GNOME Quick Start}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i \chpgn }\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\headerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i Chapter 2. GNOME Quick Start}\par}{\footerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}\pard\sb373\s1\sl647 {\*\bkmkstart ID_QUICKSTART}{\*\bkmkend ID_QUICKSTART}\b\fs49\f1 Chapter 2. GNOME Quick Start\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_QUICK}{\*\bkmkend ID_QUICK}\fs41 2.1. GNOME Quick Start\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  Figure 2-1 shows an example of GNOME running. GNOME is very configurable, so your screen may look quite different. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _43}{\*\bkmkend _43}\b\lang1024 Figure 2-1. Sample GNOME Display.\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/full.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A1}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A1}The long bar at the bottom of \i Figure 2-1\i0  is a GNOME Panel, which contains a collection of useful panel applets and menus. Panel applets are tiny programs designed to be placed in a panel, for example, the clock applet on the far right shows the current time. The arrows on each side of the panel hide (and unhide) the panel. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The button in the panel containing a stylized foot is the Main Menu Button. Just click on the Main Menu Button and you'll see a menu of pre-loaded applications and actions, including a logout command. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The rest of the screen space is called the "Desktop." Just place on your desktop the items you use most often and you can double-click on an item (with the left mouse button) to use it: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19\lang1024 \'95\tab \fs24  If the item is a program, that program will start. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  If it's data, the appropriate program will be start up with that data loaded. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  If it's a directory, the file manager application will start and show the contents of that directory. Your desktop will probably have a folder icon labeled "Home directory". Double-clicking on it will start a file manager at your home directory. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312 \lang1033  The file manager application lets you manipulate your files. The left side of its window shows directories, and the right side shows the selected directory's contents: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19\lang1024 \'95\tab \fs24  To move the file or directory, just drag and drop it. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  To copy a file, hold down the \b CTRL\b0  key while dragging. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  To run a program or edit a data file, double-click it. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  To perform other operations on a file (such as rename or delete), select it using the right mouse button. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  To select more than one item at a time, click on the items after the first one while holding down the SHIFT key. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312 \lang1033  You can easily move or copy files between directories by starting two file manager applications, each one showing a different directory. If you want to put a file on your desktop, simply drag it from the file manager onto the desktop. In fact, dragging and dropping items onto other items generally "does the right thing" in GNOME, making it easy to get work done. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  GNOME is very configurable; for example, you can have multiple panels (horizontal and vertical), choose what goes in them, and have them hide automatically. There are many panel applets you can include in your panel. You can also change how the screen looks; later portions of this document tell you how. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  GNOME follows several UNIX conventions you should be aware of. The left mouse button is used to select and drag items. The right mouse button brings up a menu for the selected object (if a menu applies). Most UNIX mice have 3 buttons, and the middle button is used to paste text (if in a text area) or to move things. If you only have two buttons, press the left and right buttons simultaneously to simulate the middle button. To copy text, use the left button to drag across the text you want to copy, move to the place you want the text to be, and press the middle button. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  When an application window is displayed, there will be some buttons in its borders for controlling the window. These include buttons to minimize, maximize, and close the window. Their appearance can be configured and is controlled by a component called the "window manager." \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Two examples of border styles are the Clean style (\i Figure 2-2\i0 ) and the ICE style (\i Figure 2-3\i0 ): \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19\lang1024 \'95\tab \fs24  In the Clean border style, the underscore means minimize, the square means maximize (use the whole screen), and the X button means close the window. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  In the ICE style, the X button will close the window. Clicking the arrow with the left mouse button minimizes the window, while clicking with the right mouse button shows a menu of other options. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _86}{\*\bkmkend _86}\b Figure 2-2. Clean Border Style\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/border1.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _91}{\*\bkmkend _91}Figure 2-3. ICE Border Style\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/border2.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  If you are using a default installation of GNOME you may notice that minimizing a window actually causes that window to disappear from your desktop. To regain that window you may use the GNOME Pager, which is located on the Panel. The Pager will show you which tasks are running and where they are on your desktops. You will find the application you minimized in the task list on the right side of the GNOME Pager. Press the button for that application and it will return to your desktop. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _97}{\*\bkmkend _97}\b\lang1024 Figure 2-4. The GNOME Pager\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gnome-pager.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  You may read more about the GNOME Pager in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_APPLETSPAGER}{\fldrslt Section 11.6.4}}. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The following sections go into more detail, describing each component of the system. \hyphpar0\par\sect\sectd\plain\pgwsxn12240\pghsxn15840\marglsxn1440\margrsxn1440\margtsxn1440\margbsxn1920\headery0\footery0\pgndec\titlepg{\headerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}{\headerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i Chapter 3. Window Managers and GNOME}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i \chpgn }\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\headerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i Chapter 3. Window Managers and GNOME}\par}{\footerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}\pard\sb373\s1\sl647 {\*\bkmkstart ID_WM}{\*\bkmkend ID_WM}\b\fs49\f1 Chapter 3. Window Managers and GNOME\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_WMABOUT}{\*\bkmkend ID_WMABOUT}\fs41 3.1. About Window Managers\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The window manager is the piece of software that controls the windows in the X window environment. The placement, borders, and decorations of any window are managed by the window manager. This is very different from many other operating systems, and the way GNOME deals with window managers is different from other desktop environments. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  As stated earlier in this guide, GNOME is not dependent on any one window manager. This means that major parts of your desktop environment will not change when you decide to switch window managers. GNOME works with the window manager to give you the easiest work environment you can have. GNOME does not worry about window placement but gets information from the window manager about their placement. The GNOME Pager will only work with a GNOME compliant window manager as will drag and drop on the desktop. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  At the time of this version of the GNOME User's Guide the Enlightenment Window Manager is the only window manager that is 100% compliant. There are many other window managers that are partially compliant or are being modified to meet compliance. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Some of the window managers that have partial to full compliance at the time of this version of the GNOME User's Guide are: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19\lang1024 \'95\tab \fs24  Enlightenment - http://www.enlightenment.org \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Icewm - http://www.kiss.uni-lj.si/~k4fr0235/icewm/ \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Window Maker - http://www.windowmaker.org \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  FVWM - http://www.fvwm.org/ \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  AfterStep - http://www.afterstep.org/ \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312 \lang1033  There are a host of newer window managers being developed that will work with GNOME. You can find a list of these on the GNOME Software Map (http://www.gnome.org/applist/). \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_WMCHANGE}{\*\bkmkend ID_WMCHANGE}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 3.2. Changing Window Managers\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  At any time you may change the window manager you are using by utilizing the Window Manager Capplet in the GNOME Control Center. You may read more about this Capplet in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_GCCWM}{\fldrslt Section 9.2.4}} \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \b\fs22\lang1024\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 Keep in mind that the window manager you choose to use may not be compliant with GNOME and you may not benefit from some of the GNOME features if you use it.\hyphpar0\par\sect\sectd\plain\pgwsxn12240\pghsxn15840\marglsxn1440\margrsxn1440\margtsxn1440\margbsxn1920\headery0\footery0\pgndec\titlepg{\headerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}{\headerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i Chapter 4. Using the GNOME Panel}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i \chpgn }\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\headerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i Chapter 4. Using the GNOME Panel}\par}{\footerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}\pard\sb373\s1\sl647 {\*\bkmkstart ID_PANELUSE}{\*\bkmkend ID_PANELUSE}\b\fs49\f1 Chapter 4. Using the GNOME Panel\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart _140}{\*\bkmkend _140}\fs41 4.1. Introduction\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A2}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A2}The Panel is the heart of the GNOME interface and acts as a repository for all of your system applications, applets, and the Main Menu. The Panel is also designed to be highly configurable. The Panel gives you a place that always contains menus and applications as you want them to be. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_PANELBASIC}{\*\bkmkend ID_PANELBASIC}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 4.2. The Basics\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  Using the GNOME Panel is very simple and will come easily to anyone who has used a graphical based operating system. You may add new panels, add applications to the panel, and add various applets. All of these functions and more will be described in this section. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_PANELMENU}{\*\bkmkend ID_PANELMENU}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 4.2.1. Using the Main Menu\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A3}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A3}To start using any pre-loaded application click on the \f1 Main Menu Button\f0 . The Main Menu has the picture of the stylized foot and on first use is on the bottom left of the screen. You should release the mouse after pressing the \f1 Main Menu\f0  button so that you can take advantage of other mouse-activated features in the Main Menu such as right mouse clicks and drag and drop from the menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _155}{\*\bkmkend _155}\b Figure 4-1. The Main Menu Button\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/mm-button.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The Main Menu is the starting point for all of the applications on your system. Later in this manual you will learn how to customize the Main Menu to suit your work environment, but for now you can use the menu that is established when you install GNOME. The Main Menu works like any other menu you might have used in other graphical desktop environments. Simply press the \f1 Main Menu\f0  Button and select from the menu that pops up from the button. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_PANELHIDE}{\*\bkmkend ID_PANELHIDE}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 4.2.2. Hiding the Panel\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A4}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A4}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A5}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A5}At any time you may hide the GNOME Panel by pressing the\f1  Hide Button\f0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _172}{\*\bkmkend _172}\b Figure 4-2. The Hide Button\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/hide-button.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  This will hide the GNOME Panel in the direction of the arrow on the \f1 Hide Button\f0 . There are hide buttons on both sides of a Panel so you can hide it in either direction. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A6}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A6}You may decide that you want the Panel to hide on its own when you are not using it. This can be a helpful function if you are unable to run your system in a high resolution. You can find out how to auto hide the Panel in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_CONFPANEL}{\fldrslt Chapter 7}}. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_PANELMOVE}{\*\bkmkend ID_PANELMOVE}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 4.3. Moving and Adding Panels\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A7}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A7}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A8}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A8}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A9}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A9}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A10}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A10}Any Panel you have on your desktop can be moved by using the middle mouse button, or by simultaneously pressing the left and right mouse buttons, to drag the panel to the desired edge of your screen. If you do not have a middle mouse button and did not configure your mouse to emulate a middle button you may also move a Panel by changing its location in the Panel Configuration dialog. You can read more about this in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_CONFPANEL}{\fldrslt Chapter 7}} of this documentation. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  You may also add a new Panel to your desktop by selecting the \f1 Add New Panel\f0  from the \f1 Main Menu\f0  | \f1 Panel\f0  menu. You will be given a choice of Edge or Corner Panels. Both of these Panel types are described below. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19\lang1024 \'95\tab \fs24  Edge Panel - An Edge Panel is exactly like the main Panel that starts up with GNOME. By selecting this type of panel you may add a new Panel to another edge of your screen to give yourself more functionality. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Corner Panel - The Corner Panel is a small Panel that will not stretch across the entire edge of the screen it is on. The Corner Panel will, however, stretch to the extent needed to display the icons and applets it contains. The hide buttons work just a bit differently with Corner Panels. The hide button closest to the edge of your screen will hide the Panel as usual but the other hide button will send the whole panel to the opposite edge. When the latter move is made it will not hide the Panel since it is changing the side of the screen it resides on. If you want to hide it you will have to press the hide button once again. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312 \lang1033  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A11}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A11}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A12}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A12}At any time you can change the current panel to the opposite type by selecting either the \f1 Convert to edge panel\f0  or the \f1 Convert to corner panel\f0  from the pop-up menu. The selection that is available depends on which type of panel you right mouse click on. The selection displayed will be the opposite of the current panel. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_PANELADD}{\*\bkmkend ID_PANELADD}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 4.4. Adding Applications and Applets to the Panel\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_PANELAPPLAUNCH}{\*\bkmkend ID_PANELAPPLAUNCH}\fs34 4.4.1. Adding Application Launchers\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A13}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A13}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A14}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A14}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A15}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A15}If you would like to add an Application Launcher (an icon that starts a particular application) to the Panel, right mouse click the Panel and select\f1  Add New Launcher\f0  from the \f1 pop-up\f0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  After selecting the \f1 Add New Launcher\f0  menu item you will see a dialog which will allow you to set the properties for the application launcher you wish to add. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _237}{\*\bkmkend _237}\b Figure 4-3. The Create Launcher Dialog\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/launcher-props.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A16}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A16}In the Create launcher applet dialog you may add a name for your launcher, a comment, the command line to launch the application, and define the application type. You may also press the icon button and choose an icon to represent the application from the icon picker. If no icon is chosen a default icon will be used. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Another, quicker method of adding an application launcher to the Panel is to go into the Main Menu and right mouse click on an application menu item. You will be given another menu selection which contains \f1 Add this launcher to Panel\f0 . If you select this menu item it will automatically add a launcher for that application to the Panel in which you invoked the Main Menu. At this point you may right mouse click on the launcher and select the \f1 Properties\f0  menu item to change any options for that launcher. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_DRAWERS}{\*\bkmkend ID_DRAWERS}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 4.4.2. Grouping Items with Drawers\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A17}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A17}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A18}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A18}If you would like to group a subset of applications together you may use a Drawer. A Drawer is simply a small menu-like button that sits on your panel that groups application launchers together is one place. Once you have placed a Drawer on the Panel you may click on it to raise the menu of applications and click again to lower them. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _259}{\*\bkmkend _259}\b Figure 4-4. An open Drawer\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/drawer.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  There are a couple of ways to place a Drawer on your Panel. First you may right mouse click on the Panel and select the \f1 Add drawer\f0  from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. Second, if you want a whole subset of menus from the Main Menu to become a drawer you may right mouse click on the title bar of that menu and select the \f1 Add this as drawer to panel\f0  from the \f1 pop-up menu\f0 . \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  You can add menus to your panel in the same way you add Drawers. Menus are very similar to Drawers except that they do not use large icons to represent application launchers, instead they use a style similar to the Main Menu, i.e. small icons and the application name. You may add a menu by right mouse clicking on the title bar of a menu and select the \f1 Add this as menu to panel\f0  from the \f1 pop-up menu\f0 . You may also add system directories to the Panel as menus by dragging a directory out of the GNOME File Manager and dropping it on the Panel. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_PANELAPPLETS}{\*\bkmkend ID_PANELAPPLETS}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 4.4.3. Adding Applets\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A19}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A19}There are many applets which you can add to the Panel as well. Applets are small applications which can perform tasks within the Panel itself. There are many applets you can add to the Panel and these are covered in more detail in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_PANELAPPS}{\fldrslt Chapter 11}} of this manual. As an example of how to add an applet you can add another clock applet to your Panel. To add the clock applet to your Panel: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19\lang1024 \'95\tab \fs24  Right mouse click on the Panel \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  From the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu choose the \f1 Add new applet\f0  menu item. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  This will bring up more levels of \f1 pop-up\f0  menus. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Choose the \f1 Utility\f0  | \f1 Clock \f0 menu item. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  The Clock will be added to your Panel. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _295}{\*\bkmkend _295}\b Figure 4-5. The Clock Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/clock.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  To remove the clock applet you added you can right mouse click on the clock and select \f1 Remove from panel\f0  from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_RUNAPPS}{\*\bkmkend ID_RUNAPPS}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 4.5. Running Applications\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A20}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A20}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A21}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A21}There are many ways to launch applications within GNOME. Remember that one of GNOME's strong points is that it allows you to start and control applications with an easy-to-use graphical interface. There are many ways to start the applications you wish to use: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  As you saw in the previous section you may use the Main Menu to find applications which have been pre-loaded or you provided using the Menu Editor. You can read more about the Menu Editor in the {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_MAINMENU}{\fldrslt Chapter 8}}. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  You may also add application launchers from the Panel, which was covered in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_PANELAPPLAUNCH}{\fldrslt Section 4.4.1}}. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  If you are using the GNOME File Manager, you may double click on any executable file and it will run. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A22}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A22}You may use the GNOME Run program to launch any application. To use it select the \f1 Run program\f0  menu item from the \f1 Main Menu\f0 . This will launch a simple dialog that allows you to type in the command for launching the application. For example, if you wish to start the Emacs editor and it is not in a menu or on your panel you may select the GNOME Run Program and type \b emacs\b0  in the text box on the dialog. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_LOGOUT}{\*\bkmkend ID_LOGOUT}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 4.6. Logging Out of GNOME\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A23}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A23}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A24}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A24}GNOME has a couple of helpful methods for Logging out. You may either use the \f1 Logout\f0  menu item or the \f1 Logout\f0  button. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A25}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A25}The \f1 Logout\f0  menu item is the bottom menu item in the \f1 Main Menu\f0 . Simply select the \f1 Logout\f0  menu item and you will be prompted on whether you would like to log out or not. Select \f1 Yes\f0  and your GNOME session will end. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A26}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A26}If you would like, you may add the \f1 Logout\f0  button to the Panel. This is just another method for logging out. It provides no functionality beyond providing a pretty button. To add the \f1 Logout\f0  button to the Panel, right mouse click on the Panel and select the \f1 Add logout button\f0  menu item from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. Once the button is there you may press it to log out. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \b\fs22\lang1024\f1 NOTE: \b0 If you are running a window manager that is GNOME compliant, the logout feature will quit the window manager as well as GNOME. If you are running a non-compliant window manager you will have to end that window manager yourself.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \fs24\lang1033\f0  The Logout dialog will display when you log out of GNOME. This dialog will ask you whether or not you really want to log out. It also provides you with different methods of quitting GNOME. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  You have three choices on how to quit GNOME. You may \f1 Logout\f0  which will simply take you to a terminal; \f1 Halt\f0 , which will shut down the whole system; or \f1 Reboot\f0 , which will reboot the whole system. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  If you do not want to log out you may press the \f1 No\f0  button and you will be returned to your GNOME session. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _361}{\*\bkmkend _361}\b\lang1024 Figure 4-6. The Logout Dialog\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/logout-screen.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  Within the Logout Dialog there is one option you may choose before you leave GNOME. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  If you would like to save your current setup, you may select the \f1 Save current setup\f0  checkbox. This will save those programs you have open, and the configuration of your Panel. \hyphpar0\par\sect\sectd\plain\pgwsxn12240\pghsxn15840\marglsxn1440\margrsxn1440\margtsxn1440\margbsxn1920\headery0\footery0\pgndec\titlepg{\headerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}{\headerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i Chapter 5. The GNOME Desktop}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i \chpgn }\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\headerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i Chapter 5. The GNOME Desktop}\par}{\footerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}\pard\sb373\s1\sl647 {\*\bkmkstart ID_DESK}{\*\bkmkend ID_DESK}\b\fs49\f1 Chapter 5. The GNOME Desktop\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart _371}{\*\bkmkend _371}\fs41 5.1. Introduction\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A27}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A27}The GNOME Desktop provides the functionality of any traditional operating system desktop. You can drag files, programs and directory folders to the desktop; you can also drag those items back into GNOME-compliant applications. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \b\fs22\lang1024\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 The GNOME Desktop is actually provided by a backend process in the GNOME File Manager. If, for any reason, that backend process has stopped running you may start the GNOME File Manager again and your desktop will be restored. Even if you do have to do this you do not need to keep the GNOME File Manager window open to enable the desktop.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_DESKUSE}{\*\bkmkend ID_DESKUSE}\b\fs41 5.2. Using the Desktop\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  Using the Desktop is as simple as dragging items you wish to use routinely to the desktop. The default desktop will include a folder of your home directory (/home/[user name]). By default the GNOME File Manager window will also appear for you to access other areas of your system. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  To utilize drag and drop you need to be using either a GNOME compliant application or a Motif application. GNOME is compliant with Motif drag and drop so you will find it works with many applications you already have installed. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  All items that are stored on your desktop are located in the following directory: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl281 \fs21\f2      \fs19 $\fs21 /home/[user name]/.gnome-desktop/  \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
    \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \fs24\f0  This is helpful to remember when you want your desktop to contain an item for which you can not utilize drag and drop. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A28}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A28}Once you have started GNOME you will notice that any drives you have connected to your system will be shown on your desktop with the appropriate icons. You may mount and access these drives utilizing these icons. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \b\fs22\lang1024\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 You must have permission to mount the device shown on your desktop before you can utilize these icons. If you do not have mount permission someone with root access such as your system administrator can give it as follows.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl286 {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A29}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A29} Giving mount access to ordinary users can be done quite easily if you have \i linuxconf\i0  installed on your machine. Just select the drive you want to access in the Access local drive section. In the Options tab select the User Mountable option. Your drive will now be mountable by users.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl286 If \i linuxconf\i0  is not available someone with root access must edit the \i /etc/fstab\i0  file to include user access. This is done by adding the user attribute to the drive. For Example:\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl286 If your fstab file contains a line like this: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl257 \fs19\f2        /dev/cdrom /mnt/cdrom iso9660 exec,dev,ro,noauto 0 0\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
      \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \fs22\f1  Add "user" to the fourth column: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl257 \fs19\f2       /dev/cdrom /mnt/cdrom iso9660 user,exec,dev,ro,noauto 0 0\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
     \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \fs22\f1 Depending on your system and work environment, there could be some security risks in permitting users to mount disks. Please consult your system administrator before taking this action.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \fs24\lang1033\f0  Once you have permission to mount a drive you may right mouse click on the drive icon on your desktop. This will bring up a small pop-up menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  You may select \f1 Mount device\f0  to mount it and \f1 Eject device\f0  to eject it. Once it is mounted you may either double-click it or choose \f1 Open\f0  from the pop-up menu to open and GNOME File Manager window viewing the contents of the device. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  If you are missing any drives that might have been added to your machine you may right mouse click on an empty space on the desktop and choose the \f1 Recreate Desktop Shortcuts \f0 menu item from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_DESKAREAS}{\*\bkmkend ID_DESKAREAS}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 5.3. Desktop Areas\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A30}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A30}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A31}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A31}Desktop areas allow you to keep a well organized system when you have many tasks to perform at one time. Just like adding a new desk when you have too much material to fit on one, desktop areas allow you to move to another area to launch more programs. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  GNOME is aware of desktop areas even though they are controlled by another software program called the 'window manager'. You can set the number of desktop areas within the configuration of the window manager you are using. If you are using the default window manager or your window manager has a graphical configuration tool you may be able to launch it from the Window Manager Capplet. You may read more about this Capplet in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_GCCWM}{\fldrslt Section 9.2.4}} \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \b\fs22\lang1024\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 Most window managers will give you the option of having multiple desktops, which are different from desktop areas. Desktop areas are virtual extensions of one desktop whereas multiple desktops are actually separate.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl286 The default setup of GNOME is to use desktop areas with only one desktop. The reason for this is with some applications, such as those which use Motif, users can experience problems with some drag and drop functionality across desktops.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_DESKMENUS}{\*\bkmkend ID_DESKMENUS}\b\fs41 5.4. Other Desktop Menus\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A32}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A32}There are a few desktop menus you may use in GNOME. These menus are accessed by making a right-button mouse click on any clean space on the desktop. This will bring up a \f1 pop-up\f0  menu which contains a few items: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19\lang1024 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 New | Terminal\f0  - This launches a new GNOME Terminal window that will automatically navigate to the ~/.gnome-desktop directory. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 New | Directory\f0  - This creates a new directory on your desktop into which you can place files: a convenient way to clean up your desktop. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 New | Launcher\f0  - This allows you to place a new application launcher on the desktop. When selected, this menu item will launch an \f1 Application Launcher\f0  dialog that allows you to specify which application and its properties. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 New | [application]\f0  - Some applications may put items for you in the \f1 New\f0  menu. For example, the Gnumeric spreadsheet will put a \f1 New Gnumeric Spreadsheet\f0  menu item in the \f1 New\f0  menu so you can start up a new spreadsheet easily. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Arrange Icons\f0  - This automatically arranges your desktop icons. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Create New Window\f0  - This launches a new GNOME File Manager window displaying your Home directory. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Recreate Desktop Shortcuts\f0  - This rescans the mountable devices on your machine and display an icon for any new device it might find. It also reloads any desktop items your distribution places on the desktop by default. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Rescan Desktop\f0  - This rescans the files in your ~/.gnome-desktop directory. Any new files found will be placed on the desktop as icons. \hyphpar0\par\sect\sectd\plain\pgwsxn12240\pghsxn15840\marglsxn1440\margrsxn1440\margtsxn1440\margbsxn1920\headery0\footery0\pgndec\titlepg{\headerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}{\headerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i Chapter 6. The GNOME File Manager}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i \chpgn }\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\headerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i Chapter 6. The GNOME File Manager}\par}{\footerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}\pard\sb373\s1\sl647 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GMC}{\*\bkmkend ID_GMC}\b\fs49\f1 Chapter 6. The GNOME File Manager\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart _468}{\*\bkmkend _468}\fs41 6.1. Introduction\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A33}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A33}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A34}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A34}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A35}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A35}GNOME includes a file manager that allows you to manipulate the files on your system in a comfortable, powerful, graphical environment. This File Manager is known as GMC for GNU Midnight Commander. GMC is based on the Midnight Commander file manager which can be run in a terminal. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Midnight Commander has long been known for its power and ease of use. GMC has taken the power and ease of use from MC and added the GNOME graphical frontend. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  As mentioned in the previous chapter, the GNOME File Manager provides the desktop functionality for GNOME. The GNOME File Manager also provides a place to manipulate files on your system by using the GNOME File Manager window. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _481}{\*\bkmkend _481}\b Figure 6-1. GNU Midnight Commander - The GNOME File Manager\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gmc1.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  There are two main windows within the GNOME File Manager. On the left is the tree view, which represents all of the directories on your system by their hierarchical position. On the right is the directory window, which will show you the contents of the directory which you have selected in the tree view. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  To select a directory in the tree view simply use a single mouse click. This will change the main directory view, showing the files in the directory you have chosen. If there is a plus sign to the left of a directory name in the tree window, you may click on it to show subdirectories. At this point the plus sign will have changed to a minus sign. If you click on the minus sign, the subdirectories once again become hidden in the tree view and the plus sign reappears. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A36}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A36}The directory window has a few viewing options you may wish to take advantage of: the icon view and and three list views, brief, detailed, and custom. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The Icon view is the default view and will display large icons for each file. The Brief view shows the files and directories in a list. The Detailed view expands this list to include information about the files. The Custom view is a list view that allows you to select the information you want to view about files. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  In the Brief, Detailed, and Custom views if you click on one of the information titles on the top of the window it will sort the files according to that information. For example, if you want to find the largest files in the directory you can click on the Size title and the files will be sorted by size from largest to smallest. One more click on the Size title will change the sorting from smallest to largest. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GMCNAV}{\*\bkmkend ID_GMCNAV}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 6.2. Moving Around the GNOME File Manager\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A37}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A37}Above the tree and main file windows in the GNOME File Manager there is a Location text box. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Within this text box you can type the path location of the file in which you would like to view in the main window. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A38}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A38}The GNOME File Manager is also equipped to view FTP sites. To view an FTP site you will need to be connected to the Internet either through a dial up account or a network. Type the FTP address in Location text box using and the GNOME File Manager will attempt to connect to the site. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Make sure you type in FTP addresses in the following manner: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl281 \fs21\f2 ftp://[site address]\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \fs24\f0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Above to the Location text box are navigation buttons you might wish to use. These buttons with the arrow icons allow you to move within the directories adjacent to the one you are in. The left button will take you to the previous directory you were in, the middle button will take you up one level in the directory hierarchy, and the right button will take you to the next directory if you have just moved backwards. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \b\fs22\lang1024\f1 TIP: \b0 You can open a secondary window by using your middle mouse button on any directory. Press the middle mouse button (or both left and right mouse buttons if you have emulation) on a directory in the main window and a new window will open showing the contents of the directory you clicked on.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GMCSELECT}{\*\bkmkend ID_GMCSELECT}\b\fs41 6.3. Selecting Files\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A39}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A39}Selecting files is done with your mouse by clicking on the file or files in the GNOME File Manager. The file that is selected will then highlight to show you that it has been selected. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A40}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A40}There are a couple of ways to select more than one file. One way is to use the "rubber band" select by clicking and dragging the mouse cursor around several files. This action will produce a small dotted line, the "rubber band", to show you the area in which files will be selected. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _521}{\*\bkmkend _521}\b\lang1024 Figure 6-2. "Rubber Band Select"\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/rubberband.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  If you wish to be more selective about the files you are choosing, or the files you need do not reside next to one another, you may use the \b CTRL\b0  key to keep the files you have selected while you are selecting more. This works by selecting a file, pressing and holding the \b CTRL\b0  key and selecting another file. While the \b CTRL\b0  key is pressed you will be able to add to the "list" of files that are selected. Once you have selected multiple files by either method you may copy or move the files. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  You may also select all files in a directory by selecting the \f1 Select All\f0  menu item from the \f1 Edit\f0  menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A41}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A41}You may also filter your selection by using the \f1 Select Files\f0  menu item in the \f1 Edit\f0  menu. Using \f1 Select Files\f0  will display a simple dialog which will allow you to type in criteria for your selection. In this field, the symbol \b *\b0  is interpreted as a wildcard, E.g., it matches any string. For example, if you would like to select all files in the directory that start with the letter \b D\b0 , you can type \b D*\b0  (note that filenames in Unix are case-sensitive). \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GMCCOPY}{\*\bkmkend ID_GMCCOPY}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 6.4. Copying and Moving Files\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A42}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A42}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A43}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A43}The default action for dragging and dropping files between the GNOME File Manager and the desktop is to move them. But you can also use drag and drop to copy a file by pressing the \b SHIFT\b0  key while dragging the file(s). You can also drag a file within the file manager to another directory. Select the file in the main window and drag it to the desired directory in the tree window. Note, however, that when dragging to the tree window the default action is to copy the file. As you drag the file to the tree window, you will see a plus sign appear to remind you that the file will be copied. You can also use drag and drop to copy directories the same way as you did for files. Again note the plus sign signifying that the directory will be copied not moved \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A44}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A44}You may also bring up a menu which lets you decide what action to perform with a drag by using the middle mouse button to drag a file or pressing the \b ALT\b0  Key while dragging a file. Once you release the drag you will get a pop-up menu which contains the options Copy, Move, Link, and Cancel Drag. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _559}{\*\bkmkend _559}\b Figure 6-3. The Move Dialog\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gmc_move.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A45}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A45}To use the move dialog you simply type in the path where you wish to move the file. If you want to rename the file you may type the new name of the file in the path string. The Copy dialog looks and works exactly the same way as the Move/rename dialog. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  If the file you are moving is a symbolic link \'97 that is, a virtual link to where the file actually resides (called a shortcut in some other operating systems) \'97 you may select the \f1 Advanced Options\f0  tab and select \f1 Preserve symlinks\f0 . Selecting this will make sure the link is preserved despite the move. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  It is recommended that you use this method of moving a symbolic link. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GMCRENAME}{\*\bkmkend ID_GMCRENAME}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 6.5. Renaming Files\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A46_45_A}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A46_45_A}Renaming files in the GNOME File Manager window or on the desktop can be achieved in two ways. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  One method of renaming a file is to right mouse click on the file and choose the \f1 Properties\f0  menu item from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. In the Filename text box you may type in the new name as you wish it to appear. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _580}{\*\bkmkend _580}\b\lang1024 Figure 6-4. File Properties\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/fileprops.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  A shortcut method to rename a file is to slowly double click on the filename in the icon view or on the desktop. Make sure the double-click is slow so you do not launch the file but you simply highlight and then click again. At this point the name of the file will enter into the editing mode, your mouse cursor will change to an editing line, and you can type in the new name. Once the name is as you would like it to be you may press the \b Enter\b0  key to end the editing process. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GMCLAUNCH}{\*\bkmkend ID_GMCLAUNCH}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 6.6. Launching Applications From the GNOME File Manager\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A46}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A46}The GNOME File Manager allows you to launch applications from the main window by simply double clicking your mouse on a file which has an application associated with it. You can change the way file types are handled by reading {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_GCCMIME}{\fldrslt Section 9.4}} \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A47}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A47}If the file does not have an associated application you can right mouse click on the file and select \f1 Open with\f0  from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. This will bring up a dialog which that you to define the application which will launch the file. For example, if you want to edit a file names test.txt with Emacs (a popular text editor) you can right mouse click on test.txt and choose \f1 Open with\f0 . When you get the Open with dialog box simply type in emacs in front of the test.txt file name. When you press \f1 OK\f0  Emacs will open the file. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _604}{\*\bkmkend _604}\b\lang1024 Figure 6-5. The Open With Dialog\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/open_with.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GMCFILEPROPS}{\*\bkmkend ID_GMCFILEPROPS}\fs41\f1 6.7. File Properties and Actions\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A48}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A48}For any file in the main file display you may right mouse click on it and choose a variety of properties and actions for it from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19\lang1024 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Open\f0  - This will open the file with the default application associated with it. You may read more about editing these associations in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_GCCMIME}{\fldrslt Section 9.4}}. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Open With\f0  - You may open a file with any application using this menu item. You may read more about this in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_GMCLAUNCH}{\fldrslt Section 6.6}}. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 View\f0  - This will view the file with a basic text viewer. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Edit\f0  - This will launch an editor to edit the file. The editor launched is determined by the application associated with that file type. You may read more about editing this association in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_GCCMIME}{\fldrslt Section 9.4}}. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Copy\f0  - This will copy the file to the clipboard so that it can be pasted elsewhere. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Delete\f0  - This will delete the file. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Move\f0  - This will bring up the \f1 Move\f0  dialog, which will allow you to move the file. You can read more about this dialog and moving files in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_GMCCOPY}{\fldrslt Section 6.4}}. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Symlink\f0  - Symlink allows you to create a symbolic link of the file you have selected in another directory. When you select Symlink you will see a dialog which allows you to type in the directory and filename that you wish to be the symbolic link to the file. This link will be a "shortcut" to the selected file. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Properties\f0  - The Properties menu item will launch the Properties dialog. The Properties dialog allows you to edit and view the properties for the selected file. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312 \lang1033  The Properties dialog consists of three tabs, Statistics, Options, and Permissions. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1200\sl312 \b\lang1024 Figure 6-6. File Properties\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1200{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/fileprops.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \b0\fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Statistics\f0  - This tab will show you the file information including the name, type, size, and history. You may change the name of the file in the \f1 File Name\f0  text box. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Options\f0  - This tab will allow you to change the action options for the file. You can define how to open, view, and edit the file. If you need to open it in a terminal window you may select the \f1 Needs terminal to run\f0  checkbox. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1920\sl286 \b\fs22\f1 NOTE: \b0 If you bring up the Properties dialog from an icon on the desktop you will be able to change the icon for that file in the Options tab.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17\f0 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Permissions\f0  - This tab allows you to change the permissions and ownership of a file if you have access to do so. You may select Read, Write, and Exec permissions for the User, Group, and Others. You may also set the UID, GID and Sticky as well as define who owns the file. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GMCPREFS}{\*\bkmkend ID_GMCPREFS}\b\fs41\f1 6.8. Changing Your Preferences in The File Manager\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A49}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A49}There are many settings you can configure for the GNOME File Manager. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  These settings may be accessed from the \f1 GMC Preferences\f0  dialog. You may launch this dialog by selecting the \f1 Preferences\f0  menu item from the \f1 Settings\f0  menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The \f1 GMC Preferences\f0  dialog is divided into Five major sections: \f1 File Display\f0 , \f1 Confirmation\f0 , \f1 VFS\f0 , \f1 Caching \f0 , \f1 Desktop\f0 , and \f1 Custom View\f0 . \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GMCPREFS_45_FILE}{\*\bkmkend ID_GMCPREFS_45_FILE}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 6.8.1. File Display\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _691}{\*\bkmkend _691}\fs24\f0 Figure 6-7. File Display Preferences\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gmcprops1.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \b0\fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  The \f1 File Display\f0  tab allows you to change the way files are displayed in GMC. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Show backup files\f0  - This will show any backup file that might be on your system. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Show hidden files\f0  - This will show all "dot files" or files that begin with a dot. This files typically include configuration files and directories. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Mix files and directories\f0  - This option will display files and directories in the order you sort them instead of always having directories shown above files. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Use shell patterns instead of regular expressions\f0  - This option is for advanced users only. If you are unfamiliar with Regular Expressions you should not use this option. If you are familiar with how to create regular expressions you may select this option to use them in your sorts and filters. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GMCPREFS_45_CONFIRM}{\*\bkmkend ID_GMCPREFS_45_CONFIRM}\b\fs34\f1 6.8.2. Confirmation\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _724}{\*\bkmkend _724}\fs24\f0 Figure 6-8. Confirmation Preferences\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gmcprops2.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \b0\fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  This tab allows you to change which functions ask for your confirmation before continuing. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Confirm when deleting file\f0  - This will bring up a confirmation screen before deleting a file. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Confirm when overwriting files\f0  - This will bring up a confirmation screen before overwriting a file. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Confirm when executing files\f0  - This will bring up a confirmation screen before executing a file. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Show progress while operations are being performed\f0  - This will bring up a progress bar while certain operations are being performed such as copying, moving, deleting, etc. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GMCPREFS_45_VFS}{\*\bkmkend ID_GMCPREFS_45_VFS}\b\fs34\f1 6.8.3. VFS\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _750}{\*\bkmkend _750}\fs24\f0 Figure 6-9. VFS Preferences\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gmcprops3.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \b0\fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  This tab allows you to configure the options for your Virtual File System. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312 \lang1033  The Virtual File System allows you to manipulate files that are not located on your local file system. There are different version of the VFS including ftpfs and tarfs. The ftpfs allows you to work on FTP sites while the tarfs gives you access inside .tar files. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1680\sl286 \b\fs22\lang1024\f1 NOTE: \b0 The .tar file is the standard UNIX archive format\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17\f0 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 VFS Timeout\f0  - This will determine how long you will be connected to any VFS without activity. The timeout is measured in seconds. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Anonymous FTP password\f0  - This allows you to set a password for logging into anonymous FTP sites. Usually you will want to make this your email address. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Always use FTP proxy\f0  - If you need to use a proxy to connect to FTP sites you will want to enable this. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GMCPREFS_45_CACHE}{\*\bkmkend ID_GMCPREFS_45_CACHE}\b\fs34\f1 6.8.4. Caching\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _780}{\*\bkmkend _780}\fs24\f0 Figure 6-10. Caching Preferences\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gmcprops4.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \b0\fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  This tab allows you to configure items that will enhance the speed of GMC by using caching. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Fast directory reload\f0  - This option will store directory information in cache so that it can load faster. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1920\sl286 \b\fs22\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 If you enable the Fast directory reload you may experience problems with not seeing new files that have been added to directories.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17\f0 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Compute totals before copying files\f0  - This will make GMC determine the number of files you are copying before it performs the task so that it can give you information about the process as its happening. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 FTP directory cache timeout\f0  - This option will keep recently visited FTP site information in cache for the amount of time you specify. The time is measured in seconds. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Allow customization of icons in icon view\f0  - This will allow you to change the icons in the icon view by right mouse clicking on them and selecting the \f1 Properties\f0  menu item. You can always change the icons of items that are on your desktop but you can only change the icons in the icon view with this option turned on. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1920\sl286 \b\fs22\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 Turning on the Allow customization of icons in icon view function may result in a slower system.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GMCPREFS_45_DESK}{\*\bkmkend ID_GMCPREFS_45_DESK}\b\fs34 6.8.5. Desktop\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A55A}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A55A}As you learned before, the GNOME desktop is controlled by the GNOME File Manager. The Desktop Dialog allows you to change the settings of the desktop. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _816}{\*\bkmkend _816}\b\lang1024 Figure 6-11. The Desktop Dialog\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gmcprops5.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  \f1 Icon placement\f0  - This small window allows you to determine where your desktop icons will be placed by default. To change the location of the icons simply click your mouse button in the window near the edge you would like the icons to appear. The small sample icons will move with your mouse clicks to show you where the default placement will be. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  \f1 Use shaped icons\f0  - This option is turned on by default. If for some reason you have and older display, a strange X server setup, or any other graphic display problem, you may select this to make the desktop icons non-transparent. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  \f1 Use shaped text\f0  - This option is turned on by default. Like the shaped icons above you may choose to have non-transparent text labels with your icons. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  \f1 Auto icon placement\f0  - This will automatically arrange icons on your desktop for you. If you would rather place the icons manually you should turn this off. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  \f1 Snap icons to grid\f0  - This will keep all of your icons in line when you move them to keep a clean desktop. It creates a grid that the icons will automatically move to when you release it after dragging. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GMCPREFS_45_CUSTOM}{\*\bkmkend ID_GMCPREFS_45_CUSTOM}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 6.8.6. Custom View\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A56}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A56}The Custom View dialog allows you to set the way you would like the Custom View to look in the GNOME File Manager. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _837}{\*\bkmkend _837}\b\lang1024 Figure 6-12. The Custom View Dialog\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/custom-view.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  There are two main columns in the \f1 Custom View\f0 , the \f1 Possible Columns\f0  and the \f1 Displayed Columns\f0 . \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The \f1 Possible Columns\f0  list includes all of the information types that can be displayed. If you would like to include one, you may press the \f1 Add\f0  button and it will be added to the \f1 Displayed Columns\f0  list. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The \f1 Displayed Columns\f0  list shows you the current information types that will be included in your Custom View. If you wish to remove any you may press the \f1 Remove\f0  button. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  If you would like to re-arrange the items in the \f1 Displayed Columns\f0  list you may drag them to the desired location with your mouse. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GMCMENUS}{\*\bkmkend ID_GMCMENUS}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 6.9. Menu Guide to the GNOME File Manager\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A57}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A57}In this section each menu item in the GNOME File Manager will be described. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \b\fs22\lang1024\f1 Tip: \b0 All menus in the GNOME File Manager are enabled with the tear-away feature. If you would like any menu to "float" on the desktop in its own window simply select the perforation line at the top of the menu.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19\f0 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 File\f0  - The File Menu contains items associated with files and higher level activity. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Create New Window\f0  - This will open a new File Manager Window. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 New | Terminal\f0  - This launches a new GNOME Terminal window that will automatically navigate to the directory displayed in the main window view. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 New | Directory\f0  - This creates a new directory in the directory displayed in the main window view. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 New | [application]\f0  - Some applications may put items for you in the \f1 New\f0  menu. For example, the Gnumeric spreadsheet will put a \f1 New Gnumeric Spreadsheet\f0  menu item in the \f1 New\f0  menu so you can a new spreadsheet in the directory displayed in the main window view. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Open\f0  - This will open the file you have selected with your mouse cursor. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Copy\f0  - This will launch the Copy dialog to enable you to copy the selected file to a destination you choose. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Delete\f0  - This will delete the file you have selected. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Move\f0  - This will launch the Move/rename dialog to enable you to rename the selected file or move it to a destination you choose. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Show directory sizes\f0  - This option will determine the size of your directories and display it in the Detail or Custom views. Depending on the size of your directories, this could take a while to display and may tax your system when viewing large directories. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Close this Window\f0  - This will close the GNOME File Manager window you are currently running. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Edit\f0  - The Edit menu contains items that are associated with editing and selecting files. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Select All\f0  - This will select all of the files in the main window. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Select Files\f0  - This will launch a simple dialog box which will allow you to specify a selection pattern. For Example, if you wish to select all files beginning with the letter D you can simple type D* and press OK. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Invert Selection\f0  - This will invert the current selection. For example, if you have 7 files selected in a directory with 10 files, selecting Invert Selection will select the three remaining files and unselect the 7 files that were previously selected. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Search\f0  - This toggles on the "completion" search for the File Manager. Once it is turned on the status bar at the bottom of the window displays the word "Search:" and allows you to start typing. If you are searching for a file named "GNU" in the directory displayed in the main window view typing "G" will move the selection to the first file or directory beginning with "G". Typing "GN" move the selection to the first file beginning with "GN", and so on. You may also toggle this feature on by pressing \b CTRL\b0 -\b S\b0 .To end the search you may select the file or directory or simply navigate away from the file with the arrow keys or your mouse. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Rescan Directory\f0  - This will rescan the current directory in case the files in the directory have changed. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Settings\f0  - This contains the Preferences menu item. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Preferences\f0  - This will launch the Preferences dialog so that you can customize the GNOME File Manager. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Layout\f0  - This menu contains items that are associated with the layout in GNOME File Manager. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Sort By\f0  - This will launch a dialog box which will allow you to select how you wish the files to be sorted in the current directory. You may sort by one of the following: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1680\sl312\fi-240 \tx1680 \~\tab Name\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1680\sl312\fi-240 \tx1680 \~\tab File Type\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1680\sl312\fi-240 \tx1680 \~\tab Size\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1680\sl312\fi-240 \tx1680 \~\tab Time Last Accessed\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1680\sl312\fi-240 \tx1680 \~\tab Time Last Modified\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1680\sl312\fi-240 \tx1680 \~\tab Time Last Changed\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Filter View\f0  - This will bring up a simple dialog which allows you to view only files with names matching a pattern. For example, if you wish to only view files in the directory that start with the letter D you can type D* into the dialog and press OK. If you wish to see all files again you will need to launch the Filter View dialog again and clear the dialog or type in a *. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Icon View\f0  - Selecting this will display the files in the main window as large icons. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Partial View\f0  - Selecting this will display the files in the main window as a list with only file names. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Full View\f0  - Selecting this will display the files in the main window as a list with all file information. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Custom View\f0  - The \f1 Custom View\f0  menu item switches the main window to the Custom View which is a list view displaying the information about your files that you specify. To customize the Custom view you will need to use the \f1 Custom View Editor\f0  in the \f1 Preferences\f0  dialog. You may read more about the \f1 Preferences\f0  dialog in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_GMCPREFS}{\fldrslt Section 6.8}}. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Commands\f0  - The Command menu contains items that are commands to run on files in the GNOME File Manager. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Find File\f0  - Find File brings up a dialog which allows you to search for particular files on your system. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Edit mime types\f0  - This option will launch the GNOME Control Center Capplet that allows you to edit Mime Types for GNOME. Mime types determine, among other things, what application will handle particular file types. You can read more about mime types in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_GCCMIME}{\fldrslt Section 9.4}} \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Run Command\f0  - This menu item allows you to run a command from GMC. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Run Command in panel\f0  - This menu item lets you run preloaded commands or commands you specify within the directory that you are currently in. Such commands might be to find SUID or SGID programs, etc. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Exit\f0  - This will allow you to exit the GNOME File Manager. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1920\sl286 \b\fs22\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 This will exit all GNOME File Manager processes which include the GNOME Desktop. If you exit you will lose all functionality on your desktop. This action is not recommended. If you wish to close the current window, use the File/Close button.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_DRAGTOUR}{\*\bkmkend ID_DRAGTOUR}\b\fs41 6.10. A Drag and Drop Tour of GNOME\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A58}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A58}There are many tips and tricks to the Desktop in GNOME. The Drag and Drop functionality extends to many areas of GNOME making it easy to interconnect GNOME in many interesting ways. Below is a series of tips and tricks to using GNOME Drag and Drop. This is a good tour of GNOME and will show you how to utilize GNOME to its fullest extent. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19\lang1024 \'95\tab \fs24  Drag a Color onto the Panel - Whenever you have a color selector displayed you may drag a color from the selected color bar to the Panel and it will change the Panel to that color. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Drag a Pixmap to the Background Selector - If you would like to change the background to an image, you can drag that image from your GNOME File Manager to the Monitor Image in the Background Capplet of the Control Center and it will change to that image. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Drag to an Application - Many GNOME compliant applications will accept drag and drop. If you would like to open a file in Gnumeric, a GNOME compliant spreadsheet application, you may simply drag the file from the GNOME File Manager onto Gnumeric and it will open the file. The same is true for applications built using Motif. You may drag a saved URL onto Netscape 4x and it will open the URL. This can be very useful if you are working within the GNOME File Manager and wish to quickly open a file. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Adding an Application Launcher to the Panel - If you would like to add an application launcher to the Panel you may drag and drop any executable file from the GNOME File Manager, or the Desktop, onto the Panel. This will display the Create Launcher applet dialog box which will allow you to select a name and an icon for that launcher. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Dragging Files - There are many ways to use drag and drop to help you manage your system. You can open two GNOME File Manager windows selecting two different directories then drag files between the two windows to copy, move, or link files. You can drag files from the File Manager to the desktop to make it more accessible. Use the middle mouse button or the right and left mouse buttons together and Drag a directory folder to the desktop. Choose the link option from the pop-up menu to make a link to the desktop. This will give you a quick way to launch the File Manager to that directory. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Dragging Directories - You can drag a directory out of the GNOME File Manger and place it on the Panel. This will create a new menu which allows you easy access to the files in that directory. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  You may drag any sub menu from the Main Menu to the panel and a new menu launcher is added to the panel. This allows easier access to that sub-set of menus. \hyphpar0\par\sect\sectd\plain\pgwsxn12240\pghsxn15840\marglsxn1440\margrsxn1440\margtsxn1440\margbsxn1920\headery0\footery0\pgndec\titlepg{\headerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}{\headerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i Chapter 7. Configuring the Panel}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i \chpgn }\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\headerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i Chapter 7. Configuring the Panel}\par}{\footerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}\pard\sb373\s1\sl647 {\*\bkmkstart ID_CONFPANEL}{\*\bkmkend ID_CONFPANEL}\b\fs49\f1 Chapter 7. Configuring the Panel\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart _1022}{\*\bkmkend _1022}\fs41 7.1. Introduction\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A59}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A59}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A60}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A60}The GNOME Panel is highly configurable and comes equipped with many graphical tools to help you do the configuration. In this section you will learn how to configure any GNOME Panel the way you would like it. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_CONFGLOBAL}{\*\bkmkend ID_CONFGLOBAL}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 7.2. Global Panel Properties\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A61}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A61}To start configuring the GNOME panel right click on the panel and select the \f1 Global Properties\f0  menu item. You may also press the \f1 Main Menu\f0  button and select the \f1 Panel\f0  | \f1 Global Properties\f0  menu item. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  This will bring the Global Panel Configuration dialog up. With this dialog you can set properties that will affect all Panels you use now and any panels you add in the future. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1042}{\*\bkmkend _1042}\b Figure 7-1. The Global Panel Configuration Dialog\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/global-config.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The Global Panel Configuration Dialog contains six tabs which help you configure the global properties of the GNOME Panel: Animation, Launcher Icon, Drawer Icon, Menu Icon, and Miscellaneous. Each of these tabs is explained below. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_ANIMTAB}{\*\bkmkend ID_ANIMTAB}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 7.2.1. Animation Tab\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \b0\fs19\f0 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Enable animations\f0  - This allows the animations configurable on this tab to be visible. The animations must be enabled to use the other features of this tab. The default position is on. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Auto-Hide Animation Speed\f0  - If you have the panel hiding automatically this will control how fast it occurs. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Explicit-Hide Animation Speed\f0  - This controls the hide speed when you press the Panel's Hide Button. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Drawer Animation Speed\f0  - If you use a Drawer panel this will control how fast the drawer menu will raise. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Auto-Hide Minimize Delay(ms)\f0  - If you have the Panel set to minimize automatically this will allow you to control how much time passes before it minimizes. The Panel will start the time count once the mouse is no longer over it. It will appear again when the mouse is passed over the portion of the Panel that remains visible. This time is measured in milliseconds. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Auto-Hide Minimized Size(pixels)\f0  - If you have the Panel hiding automatically this determines the number of pixels that will show while the Panel is minimized. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_LAUNCHTAB}{\*\bkmkend ID_LAUNCHTAB}\b\fs34\f1 7.2.2. Launcher icon Tab\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \b0\fs19\f0 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Tiles enabled\f0  - This checkbox will enable background tiles for all icons on the Panel. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Tile filename (up)\f0  - This is the name and path of the image file you wish to use for the tile in the up position (inactive, not pressed) You may press the \f1 Browse\f0  button to search for the file. Launcher tiles must be enabled to access this option. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Tile filename (down)\f0  - This is the name and path of the image file you wish to use for the tile in the down position (active, pressed). You may press the \f1 Browse\f0  button to search for the file. Launcher tiles must be enabled to access this option. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Border width (tile only)\f0  - This determines the width of the border around an icon. This is very useful if you have an icon that would normally cover up a tile. You can set the border to a smaller size and still be able to see your tile. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Depth (displacement when pressed)\f0  - This determines the depth an icon will displace when pressed. Launcher tiles must be enabled to access this option. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_DRAWERTAB}{\*\bkmkend ID_DRAWERTAB}\b\fs34\f1 7.2.3. Drawer icon Tab\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \b0\fs19\f0 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Tiles enabled\f0  - This checkbox will enable background tiles for all drawers on the Panel. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Tile filename (up)\f0  - This is the name and path of the image file you wish to use for the tile in the up position(inactive, not pressed) You may press the \f1 Browse\f0  button to search for the file. Drawer tiles must be enabled to access this option. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Tile filename (down)\f0  - This is the name and path of the image file you wish to use for the tile in the down position(active, pressed) You may press the \f1 Browse\f0  button to search for the file. Drawer tiles must be enabled to access this option. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Border width (tile only)\f0  - This determines the width of the border around a tile. Drawer tiles must be enabled to access this option. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Depth (displacement when pressed)\f0  - This determines the depth a tile will displace when pressed. Drawer tiles must be enabled to access this option. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_MENUTAB}{\*\bkmkend ID_MENUTAB}\b\fs34\f1 7.2.4. Menu icon Tab\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \b0\fs19\f0 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Tiles enabled\f0  - This checkbox will enable background tiles for the \f1 Main Menu\f0  button on the Panel. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Tile filename (up)\f0  - This is the name and path of the image file you wish to use for the tile in the up position (inactive, not pressed) You may press the \f1 Browse\f0  button to search for the file. Menu tiles must be enabled to access this option. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Tile filename (down)\f0  - This is the name and path of the image file you wish to use for the tile in the down position(active, pressed) You may press the \f1 Browse\f0  button to search for the file. Menu tiles must be enabled to access this option. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Border width (tile only)\f0  - This determines the width of the border around a tile. Menu tiles must be enabled to access this option. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Depth (displacement when pressed)\f0  - This determines the depth a tile will displace when pressed. Menu tiles must be enabled to access this option. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_LOGOUTTAB}{\*\bkmkend ID_LOGOUTTAB}\b\fs34\f1 7.2.5. Logout Icon Tab\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \b0\fs19\f0 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Tiles enabled\f0  - This checkbox will enable background tiles for all Logout buttons on the Panel. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Tile filename (up)\f0  - This is the name and path of the image file you wish to use for the tile in the up position (inactive, not pressed) You may press the \f1 Browse\f0  button to search for the file. Logout button tiles must be enabled to access this option. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Tile filename (down)\f0  - This is the name and path of the image file you wish to use for the tile in the down position (active, pressed) You may press the \f1 Browse\f0  button to search for the file. Logout button tiles must be enabled to access this option. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Border width (tile only)\f0  - This determines the width of the border around a tile. Logout button tiles must be enabled to access this option. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Depth (displacement when pressed)\f0  - This determines the depth a tile will displace when pressed. Logout button tiles must be enabled to access this option. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_MISCTAB}{\*\bkmkend ID_MISCTAB}\b\fs34\f1 7.2.6. Miscellaneous Tab\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \b0\fs19\f0 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Tooltips enabled\f0  - This enables tooltips for items on the panel. Tooltips are pop-up help dialogs that appear when you mouse is over an element on the panel. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Show Small Icons\f0  - This will show small icons in the Main Menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Show ... buttons\f0  - This will enable three small dots to appear on Main Menu items that launch dialogs. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Show popup menus outside of panels\f0  - When this button is on it allows popup menus to appear away from the Panel. When toggled off, the popups will appear over the Panel. This can be useful on smaller screens or cluttered desktops. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Keep menus in memory\f0  - This will keep your menus in memory so that they do not rescan for added items. This can increase the speed of GNOME, but may also result in you missing new items added to your menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Switched movement\f0  - This allows launcher buttons on the panel to switch places with other icons when being moved. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Free Movement (doesn't disturb other applets)\f0  - This feature locks the arrangement of your icons on the Panel (except the on you are moving). This is a good feature to use if you like the way your icons are arranged. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Prompt before logout\f0  - This will bring up a yes/no dialog that asks you if you would really like to log out. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Raise panels on mouse-over\f0  - If you are using a window manager that is not GNOME compliant it will not understand its relationship with the Panel. This can cause your Panel to be covered by applications. If you enable this feature you can have the Panel automatically raise when your mouse is over it. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Keep panel below windows\f0  - If you are using a GNOME compliant window manager the window manager will understand its relationship with the Panel. If you choose this feature the window manager and GNOME will allow applications to appear over the Panel. This can be useful on smaller screens. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Close drawer if a launcher inside it is pressed\f0  - By default drawers will remain open when you select an item within one. This can be annoying as the drawer will remain open until you close it with a mouse click. With this option selected drawers will close automatically when you select any item within one. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Applet padding\f0  - This changes the amount of space (padding) between icons and applets. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_CONFTHIS}{\*\bkmkend ID_CONFTHIS}\b\fs41\f1 7.3. This Panel Properties\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A62}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A62}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A63}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A63}Each Panel's properties can be configured individually. To change the configuration of the active Panel, right mouse click on the Panel and select the \f1 This panel properties\f0  menu item from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. You may also press the \f1 Main Menu\f0  button and select the \f1 Panel\f0  | \f1 This panel properties\f0  menu item. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  This will bring up the Panel properties dialog box. In this box you can change the properties for the active Panel. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1204}{\*\bkmkend _1204}\b\lang1024 Figure 7-2. This Panel Properties Dialog\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/thispanel.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  The Panel properties dialog contains two tabs to help you set the active Panel properties: Edge Panel and Background. Both of these tabs are explained below. If you have converted the panel to a corner panel, which is accomplished by selecting this item in the main menu, a Corner Panel tab will replace the Edge Panel tab. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_EDGETAB}{\*\bkmkend ID_EDGETAB}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 7.3.1. Edge Panel Tab\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \b0\fs19\f0 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Position\f0  - This changes the position of the Panel on the screen. You may select either Top, Right, Left or Bottom. The Panel will change position once you have pressed the \f1 Apply\f0  button. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Minimize Options\f0  - The options here will enable you to either Explicitly hide the Panel yourself using the hide buttons or have it Auto Hide when the mouse is not over the Panel. If you choose to Auto Hide you might want to Disable the hide buttons here as well. You may also disable the hide button arrows graphics on the Panel as well. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_PANELBACKTAB}{\*\bkmkend ID_PANELBACKTAB}\b\fs34\f1 7.3.2. Background Tab\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \b0\fs19\f0 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Background\f0  - These options allow you to change the background of the Panel itself. You may choose, if you wish, to have the standard, Pixmap, or Color background. The standard look for the Panel is determined by the GTK theme you are running at the time. The Pixmap option allows you to choose an image to tile or scale to the Panel. The Color option allows you to specify a particular color for the Panel. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \b\fs22\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 An easier way to change the background of your panel is to drag and drop an image file from the GNOME File Manager onto the Panel. This will automatically change the background of the panel to that image.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19\f0 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Image file\f0  - If you wish to have a Pixmap for the background of your Panel this section of the dialog is where you choose which image to use. If you press the \f1 Browse\f0  button you can search for the file you want to use. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Scale image to fit panel\f0  - This allows a background image to scale to the size of the panel. If it is not checked, images will tile to the panel. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Background color\f0  - If you choose to have your Panel one color this button will launch a dialog which allows you to specify which color to use. \hyphpar0\par\sect\sectd\plain\pgwsxn12240\pghsxn15840\marglsxn1440\margrsxn1440\margtsxn1440\margbsxn1920\headery0\footery0\pgndec\titlepg{\headerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}{\headerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i Chapter 8. Editing the Main Menu}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i \chpgn }\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\headerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i Chapter 8. Editing the Main Menu}\par}{\footerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}\pard\sb373\s1\sl647 {\*\bkmkstart ID_MAINMENU}{\*\bkmkend ID_MAINMENU}\b\fs49\f1 Chapter 8. Editing the Main Menu\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart _1248}{\*\bkmkend _1248}\fs41 8.1. Introduction\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A66}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A66}The Main Menu is a repository for your applications and can be found on the Panel. The Main Menu is preloaded with GNOME but is can be configured to fit your work habits. The Main Menu is broken up into two main subdirectories: the System menus and the User menus. The Menu Editor is available for you to add new applications to the Main Menu but you can not add applications to the System menus if you are not system administrator (root). In this section you will learn how to configure the Main Menu with applications you wish to use everyday. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_MENUCONF}{\*\bkmkend ID_MENUCONF}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 8.1.1. Configuring the Main Menu\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A67}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A67}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A68}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A68}If you want to change properties of the Main Menu or any other menu you have on your Panel you may right click on the menu button and select \f1 Properties\f0 . This will launch the \f1 Menu properties\f0  dialog. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1265}{\*\bkmkend _1265}\b\lang1024 Figure 8-1. Menu Properties Dialog\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/menu-props.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  The first selection item in the \f1 Menu properties\f0  dialog is the \f1 Menu type\f0 . This will allow you to choose for each item below whether it should be directly in the Main Menu, moved to a submenu of the Main Menu, or removed from the Main Menu entirely. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The other choices in the \f1 Menu properties\f0  dialog are sub-menu selections for Main Menus. These selections allow you to choose what is in your Main Menu which you can have in the Main Menu, in a submenu, or off: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19\lang1024 \'95\tab \fs24  System Menus - These are the menu items that are the default applications that come with GNOME. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  User Menu - This contains any menu items you added for your user account using the Menu Editor. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Another Level Menu - If you are using the Red Hat Linux distribution this is the set of applications that ship with it by default. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  KDE Menu - If you are a user of the K Desktop Environment, you may choose to include the applications included in the KDE menus. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Debian Menu - If you are using the Debian Linux distribution, this is the set of applications that ship with it by default. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_MENUEDITOR}{\*\bkmkend ID_MENUEDITOR}\b\fs34\f1 8.1.2. Using the Menu Editor\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The Menu Editor is a configuration tool for the Main Menu. It is very useful in setting up your system to your requirements. The Menu Editor is started by clicking on the Main Menu Launcher and selecting \f1 Settings\f0  | \f1 Menu editor\f0  from the \f1 Main Menu\f0 . \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  This will launch the Menu Editor. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1293}{\*\bkmkend _1293}\b Figure 8-2. The Menu Editor\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/menueditor.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The Menu Editor is divided into two main panels. The left side contains the menu in its default state. The right side contains a tabbed dialog that allows you to add new applications to the menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  On the left side in the menu tree you will notice that there are two main menu lists, one for User Menus and one for System Menus. The User Menus are for the current user and the System Menus are for all users on the system. The prepackaged applications are all located in the System Menus. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Within the menu list on the left side you may open and close folders and see what is in your current menu by clicking on the small plus signs beside the menus. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_MENUADD}{\*\bkmkend ID_MENUADD}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 8.1.3. Adding a New Menu Item\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A69}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A69}If you want to add a new menu item press the \f1 New Item\f0  button on the toolbar. A new menu item will be added to the highlighted menu is. If you do not have a menu highlighted, it will be placed at the top of the menu tree. Select the new item and type in the information for the item in the dialog on the right. Once the information is complete press the \f1 Save\f0  button and the new menu item will be inserted at the highlighted location on the left side menu tree. You may then move the menu item by pressing the up or down buttons on the toolbar. You may also move the menu item by dragging it with your left mouse button. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \b\fs22\lang1024\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 Keep in mind that you can not change the System menus unless you are logged in as root. An ordinary user can only add to, delete from, and edit the User Menus.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_MENUDRAG}{\*\bkmkend ID_MENUDRAG}\b\fs34 8.1.4. Drag and Drop in the Main Menu\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  In the Menu Editor - The Menu Editor supports drag and drop functionality, which will make your work easier. You may drag applications to the folders you wish them to reside in or re-arrange you folders completely. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  To the Panel - If you would like to place a menu item onto the Panel, you can drag and drop from the menu to the Panel and it will place a launcher there with all the appropriate properties set for you. If you prefer not to use drag and drop you may also right click on the menu item and choose the \f1 Add this launcher to panel\f0  from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. \hyphpar0\par\sect\sectd\plain\pgwsxn12240\pghsxn15840\marglsxn1440\margrsxn1440\margtsxn1440\margbsxn1920\headery0\footery0\pgndec\titlepg{\headerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}{\headerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i Chapter 9. The GNOME Control Center}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i \chpgn }\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\headerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i Chapter 9. The GNOME Control Center}\par}{\footerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}\pard\sb373\s1\sl647 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCC}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCC}\b\fs49\f1 Chapter 9. The GNOME Control Center\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart _1320}{\*\bkmkend _1320}\fs41 9.1. Introduction\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A70}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A70}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A71}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A71}The GNOME Control Center allows you to configure various parts of your system using a collection of tools called "capplets". These capplets may be associated with the core set of GNOME applications or other applications for which the developers have written capplets. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Your Control Center may contain more capplets than are documented here depending on the applications installed on your system. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The Control Center is divided into two main sections, the menu of configurable capplets and the main work space. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Working with the Control Center simply requires you to select a capplet from the menu on the left and double click on it. Once this is done, the workspace will change, allowing you to configure the item. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1332}{\*\bkmkend _1332}\b Figure 9-1. The GNOME Control Center\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/control-center.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  You may start the Control Center one of two ways. To launch the Control Center without any particular active capplet select the \f1 Control Center\f0  menu item from the \f1 Settings\f0  submenu in the Main Menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  If you know which capplet you would like to edit you may start that capplet by selecting the correct menu item in the \f1 Control Center\f0  menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCDESKTOP}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCDESKTOP}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 9.2. Desktop Capplets\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCBACK}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCBACK}\fs34 9.2.1. The Background Properties Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A72}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A72}The properties for your background image can be set here by either selecting a color or an image. If you select a color you have the option of having Solid or Gradient colors. If you choose to have Gradient colors you may choose between a Vertical or Horizontal gradient and choose the second color for the gradient to end on. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  If you decide to have an image as wallpaper you may browse for the image you wish to use. Once you have found your image you need to decide whether you would like to have the image tiled across the screen, centered, scaled up while keeping the same aspect, or simply scaled up to fit the screen. Once you have changed your background properties you may press the \f1 Try\f0  button at the bottom of the Control Center to make the change. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  If you would like to set the background by any other means you may disable this capplet by selecting \f1 Disable background selection\f0 . \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1354}{\*\bkmkend _1354}\b Figure 9-2. The Background Properties Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/bg-capplet.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCSCREEN}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCSCREEN}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 9.2.2. The Screensaver Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A73}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A73}In this capplet you can change your xscreensaver properties. This capplet contains a list of available screen savers you may choose and a demo screen. Below these two dialogs you will see a set of tools that allow you to change the settings for the global screen saver properties. If the screen saver you choose has particular settings you can change those by pressing the \f1 Settings\f0  button that appears below the Screen Saver list. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Global Screen Saver settings - In this section of the capplet you can change the time, password, and power management properties. You can decide how long you would like the screen saver to wait before starting by typing the number of minutes in the \f1 Start After\f0  text box. If you would like a password to return to your desktop click the \f1 Require Password\f0  button. Your account login password is the password set for the screen saver. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  You are also given the option of using power management -- if your monitor is capable of it. You may set the time to wait before the monitor is shut off by typing the time in the \f1 Shutdown monitor\f0  text box. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1371}{\*\bkmkend _1371}\b Figure 9-3. The Screensaver Properties Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/screensave-capplet.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCTHEME}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCTHEME}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 9.2.3. Theme Selector\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A74}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A74}The Appearances capplets contains the Theme Selector which allows you to select which GTK theme you would like to run. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  GTK themes are coordinated settings that allow the GTK widget set to change its look and feel. The widget set is the set of tools that provide buttons, scrollbars, checkboxes, etc. to applications. GNOME compliant applications use the GTK tool set so most of your GNOME applications will change their look and feel if you change the GTK theme. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  To change your GTK theme select a theme from the Available Themes list on the left side of the main workspace. If you have Auto Preview selected you will be able to see what the theme looks like in the preview window below. If you like the theme press the \f1 Try\f0  button on the bottom of the GNOME Control Center to install it. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  There are a few GTK themes that come loaded with GNOME when you install it. If you would like more themes you can check resources on the Internet like http://gtk.themes.org. Once you have found and downloaded a theme you like, press the \f1 Install new theme\f0  button. This will launch a file browser that allows you to find the theme you have just downloaded. The theme files should be in a \b tar.gz\b0  or \b .tgz\b0  format(otherwise known as a "tarball"). Once you have found the file press the \f1 OK\f0  and gnome will install the theme for you automatically. Now you can look in the Available Themes list for the theme you have installed. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Once the theme has been unpacked into the .themes directory it will be listed in the available themes window the next time you start the GNOME Control Center. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1392}{\*\bkmkend _1392}\b Figure 9-4. The Theme Selector Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/theme-select.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  If you would like to change the font used in the current theme you may do so by selecting the \f1 Use custom font\f0  checkbox and selecting the font from the font button below it. This will bring up a font selection dialog that allows you to specify the font, its style, and size. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCWM}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCWM}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 9.2.4. Window Manager Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A75}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A75}Because GNOME is not dependent on any one window manager this capplet allows you to select which window manager you wish to use. The Window Manager capplet does not determine which window managers you have available but allows you to define what, and where they are. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1406}{\*\bkmkend _1406}\b\lang1024 Figure 9-5. Window Manager Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/wm-main.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  The Window Manager capplet has a main list of the window managers that you can currently select from. Whichever window manager is active is notated by the word "Current". \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  If you wish to add a new window manager to the main list you may press the \f1 Add\f0  button. This will launch the \f1 Add New Window Manager\f0  dialog. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1415}{\*\bkmkend _1415}\b\lang1024 Figure 9-6. Add New Window Manager\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/wm-add.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  In the \f1 Add New Window Manager\f0  dialog you may specify the name you wish to give the window manager, the command to launch that window manager, and the command to launch any configuration tool that might be available for that window manager. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  If you know that the window manager is fully GNOME compliant and can be session managed you may select the \f1 Window manager is session managed\f0  button. If you are unsure you should check the documentation of your window manager. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Press \f1 OK\f0  when you are done. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Once you have finished adding your new window manager you will see it appear in the main list of window managers. If you need to change any of the properties you set in the \f1 Add New Window Manager\f0  dialog you may select the window manager from the main list with your mouse and press the \f1 Edit\f0  button. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  You may also delete any window manager in the main list by selecting it with your mouse and pressing the \f1 Delete\f0  button. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  If you are ready to switch the current window manager you may select the manager you wish to run from the main list and press the \f1 Try\f0  button. If you would like to run the configuration tool, make sure the manager you want to configure is selected and press the \f1 Run Configuration Tool for [window manager name]\f0  button. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCEDIT}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCEDIT}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 9.3. Default Editor\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A76}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A76}The Default Editor Capplet allows you to select which editor will be your default editor while using GNOME. This will allow applications like the GNOME File Manager to launch the correct editor when you try to open files associated with editing. All popular editors available are included in the selection list. This Capplet is very similar to the Mime Type Capplet but is used in association with certain applications. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1440}{\*\bkmkend _1440}\b\lang1024 Figure 9-7. The Default Editor Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gccedit.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCMIME}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCMIME}\fs41\f1 9.4. GNOME Mime Types\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A77}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A77}The GNOME Mime Types Capplet allows you to determine how you wish to handle certain file types, or Mime types. Mime stands for Multipurpose Internet Mail Extensions and was originally developed to allow email to carry various forms of data. In GNOME you can define certain Mime types to be handled in any manner you wish. For example, if you use .sgml files frequently and you wish to always use Emacs to edit them you can configure the .sgml Mime type to always be handled by Emacs. This means that any program that wishes to launch the mime type for you will bring up Emacs. This includes double clicking on the file type in the GNOME File Manager. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1451}{\*\bkmkend _1451}\b\lang1024 Figure 9-8. The GNOME Mime Types\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gccmime.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  To add a new mime type press the \f1 Add\f0  button. This will display the \f1 Add New Mime Type\f0  dialog in which you may define the new Mime type. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  To edit an existing Mime type you may select the Mime type with your mouse cursor and press the Edit button. This will bring up the \f1 Set Actions for...\f0  dialog. You may define the icon used for the Mime type, the \f1 Open\f0  action, the \f1 View\f0  action and the \f1 Edit\f0  action. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCMM}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCMM}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 9.5. Multimedia Capplets\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCC_45_KEYBELL}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCC_45_KEYBELL}\fs34 9.5.1. Keyboard Bell\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A78}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A78}{\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A79}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A79}The Keyboard Bell capplet allows you to change the bell sound that is produced by your CPU speaker when a keyboard error or message is sent. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Volume changes the actual volume of the bell. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The pitch slider will change the pitch of the note that is played. By default it is set to 440Hz, or the A above middle C. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Duration changes the length of time the tone is played. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The \f1 Test\f0  button will allow you to hear the current settings of your keyboard bell. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1480}{\*\bkmkend _1480}\b\lang1024 Figure 9-9. The Keyboard Bell Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/keybell.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCSOUND}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCSOUND}\fs34\f1 9.5.2. The Sound Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A80}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A80}The Sound capplet allows you to set the system sounds for your GNOME session. There are two tabs to select in the sound capplet: General and Sound Events. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  \f1 General Tab\f0  - At this point you have two options to choose from in the General tab, enabling sound for GNOME and for events. If you select \f1 Enable Sound for GNOME\f0  you will make sure that GNOME's sound engine (ESD) will be launched every session of GNOME you run. \f1 Enable sound for events\f0  will launch any sound files you have set in the \f1 Sound Events\f0  tab when those events occur. With these two items enabled you will utilize GNOME's session management, which will remember your sound settings whenever you log in or out. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  \f1 Sound Events Tab\f0  - This tab allows you to navigate through the sound events in GNOME and change their sounds. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  To change a sound associated with a GNOME event select the event in the hierarchical list on the left and press the \f1 Browse\f0  button to find a sound file on your system that you wish to associate with that event. Once you have found a sound file you may press the \f1 Play\f0  button to test the sound and see if you like it enough to hear it every time the event occurs. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1501}{\*\bkmkend _1501}\b Figure 9-10. The Sound Properties Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/sound-capplet.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCPERIPH}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCPERIPH}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 9.6. Peripherals\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A81}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A81}The capplets in this section of the Control Center will help you configure hardware input devices including keyboard, and mouse properties. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCKEY}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCKEY}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 9.6.1. The Keyboard Properties Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A82}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A82}There are currently two settings for the keyboard in this capplet. You may change the properties of \f1 Auto-repeat\f0  and the \f1 Keyboard Click\f0 . \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  \f1 Auto-repeat\f0  enables you to hold a key down and have it repeat the character at the rate and delay you set in this capplet. \f1 Keyboard Click\f0  enables a small click sound to play at each key press. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1523}{\*\bkmkend _1523}\b Figure 9-11. The Keyboard Properties Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/keyboard-capplet.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCMOUSE}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCMOUSE}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 9.6.2. The Mouse Properties Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A83}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A83}The Mouse Properties capplet allows you to change between left and right handed mouse buttons and to define the \f1 Accelerations\f0  and \f1 Threshold\f0  properties. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The \f1 Accelerations\f0  setting allows you to change the speed the mouse moves across the screen in relation to the movement of the mouse on your mouse pad. The \f1 Threshold\f0  setting allows you to set the speed at which you have to move your mouse before it starts the acceleration speed you have defined in the \f1 Acceleration\f0  setting. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1540}{\*\bkmkend _1540}\b Figure 9-12. The Mouse Properties Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/mouse-capplet.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCSESSION}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCSESSION}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 9.7. Session Manager\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A84}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A84}The Session Manager Capplet allows you to control the GNOME Session Management. This includes which programs start up when you log in, whether to automatically save your GNOME requests, and whether to confirm log out requests. You can find out more information about Session Management in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_SESSION}{\fldrslt Chapter 10}}. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19\lang1024 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Prompt on logout\f0  - This first option allows you to disable the confirmation dialog when logging out. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Automatically save changes to session\f0  - This will make the Session Management always save changes made to your GNOME session when you log out. If this option is not set you can still have GNOME save your session changes by checking the appropriate box in the log out confirmation dialog. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Non-session-managed Startup Programs\f0  - This allows you to start non-session managed applications whenever you start a GNOME session. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1680\sl286 \b\fs22\f1 NOTE: \b0 Programs that are not GNOME compliant are not session managed so will not be restarted without being listed here. You do not need to put GNOME applications in here, you can simply leave them running and save the current session when you log out.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1200\sl312 \fs24\lang1033\f0  If you wish to add a new program to the \f1 Non-session-managed Startup Programs\f0  press the \f1 Add\f0  button. This will launch a simple dialog that allows you to specify the command to launch the application and what priority it will receive. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312  The priority for most applications you wish to start is 50. If you have an application that needs to be started before other applications, like a window manager, you should set the priority to a lower number. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1680\sl286 \b\fs22\lang1024\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 This option is for advanced users. Unless you are familiar with the Priority settings you should keep you applications running with a Priority of 50.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19\f0 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Browse Currently Running Programs\f0  - This allows you to see what applications are currently running. You can shut down those applications if you wish and those applications will be removed from your GNOME session. The applications in this list are mostly higher level applications and should not be shut down. However, if there is a part of GNOME that you do not wish to run, like the Panel, this is where you would shut it down for now and prevent it from being started when you initiate GNOME in the future. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1680\sl286 \b\fs22\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 This option is for advanced users only. You should not use this tool shut down applications you may wish to use the next time you log in to GNOME.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1578}{\*\bkmkend _1578}\b\fs24\f0 Figure 9-13. The Session Manager Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gcc-session.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCUI}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCUI}\fs41\f1 9.8. User Interface Options\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A85}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A85}The User Interface Options allows you to change the appearance of applications that are GNOME-compliant. You may recognize these applications as ones that are pre-installed with GNOME or ones that say they are built with GTK(the GIMP Toolkit). \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCAPPDEFAULTS}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCAPPDEFAULTS}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 9.8.1. Application Defaults\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A86}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A86}The Application Defaults capplet allow you to change certain user interface aspects of your GNOME compliant applications. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \b\fs22\lang1024\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 Although this capplet gives you great control over the look and feel of your applications you should consider these tools for advanced use only.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19\f0 \'95\tab \fs24  Can detach and move menubars - By default menubars in GNOME applications may be dragged from their usual location and placed anywhere within the application or desktop. If you do not wish to use this feature you may turn it off. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Menus have relieved borders - By default menubars have relieved borders. If you do not like this look you may turn this feature off. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Submenus can be torn off - This allows the submenus to have the perforated line which allows you to "tear" them off an have them as a small movable window. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Menu items have icons - Some menu items in applications will have icons. If you wish not to see these icons in applications that use them you may turn off this feature. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Statusbar in interactive when possible - Some applications can have the status bar at the bottom become separated into its own window. If you would like to have those applications separate the status bar into another window you may turn on this option. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Statusbar progress meter on right - Some applications have progress meters in their statusbars. By default these progress meters are on the right side of the statusbar. If you wish them to be on the left you may turn off this feature. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Can detach and move toolbars - By default toolbars in GNOME applications may be dragged from their usual location and placed anywhere within the application or desktop. If you do not wish to use this feature, you may turn it off. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Toolbars have relieved border - By default toolbars have relieved borders. If you do not like this look you may turn this feature off. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Toolbar buttons have relieved border - By default toolbar buttons do not have relieved borders in their natural state. They do, however, change when the mouse is over them. If you wish them to be relieved at all times you may turn on this feature. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Toolbars have line separators - By default toolbar buttons have small line separators between them. If you so not wish to have the line separators you may turn this feature off. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Toolbars have text labels - By default toolbar buttons have images and text to identify them. If you are familiar with the buttons and do not need the text you may turn on this feature. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1621}{\*\bkmkend _1621}\b Figure 9-14. Applications Defaults Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gccappdef.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCDIALOGS}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCDIALOGS}\fs34\f1 9.8.2. Dialogs\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A87}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A87}The Dialogs Capplet will allow you to change the default settings for dialog boxes in GNOME compliant applications. A dialog box is a window that is launched by an application to help perform a task needed by that application. An example of a dialog box is a Print dialog which appears when you press a print button. The dialog allows you to set print options and start the print process. The Dialogs capplet will allow you to change the following options: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312 Dialog buttons - Choose to use the default buttons, buttons more spread out, put buttons on the edges, put the buttons on the left with left-justify, and put buttons on the right with right-justify. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Dialog buttons have icons - Some dialog buttons (for example "OK") can have icons on them. By default the applications which provide this have the icons turned on. If you wish not to see them you may turn off this feature. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Use statusbar instead of dialog when possible - You may tell applications to use the statusbar instead of a dialog if the application will allow it. This will only work with dialogs that provide information not one that require some interaction on your part. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Dialog position - This will let you choose how the dialogs appear when launched. You can let the window manager decide for you (or how you have defined it in the window manager configuration), center the dialogs on the screen, or drop them where the mouse pointer is when they are launched. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Dialog hints - This will let you change the behavior of the dialog hints which are the tooltips that appear when you move your mouse button over a button or part of the dialog. You may choose to have hints handled like other windows, or let the window manager decide how to display them. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Place dialogs over application window when possible - You may choose to place dialog over the applications when possible which will help you keep your windows organized on your screen If you are familiar with other operating systems you may wish to keep this selected as this is how most operating systems handle dialogs. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \b\fs22\lang1024\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 Although this capplet gives you great control over the look and feel of your applications you should consider these tools for advanced use only.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1641}{\*\bkmkend _1641}\b\fs24\f0 Figure 9-15. Dialog Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gccdialog.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCCMDI}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCCMDI}\fs34\f1 9.8.3. MDI\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_A88}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_A88}The MDI capplet allows you to change the MDI mode for GNOME applications. MDI stands for Multiple Document Interface and refers to the how more than one document is displayed in GNOME applications. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \b\fs22\lang1024\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 Although this capplet gives you great control over the look and feel of your applications you should consider these tools for advanced use only.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \fs24\lang1033\f0  The default style in GNOME-compliant applications for MDI is usually tabs or "notebooks" If you do not like the tab look you may change it here. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Default MDI Mode - In addition to Notebook, you will find, Toplevel and Modal. Notebook is the default tab look, Toplevel displays only the active document on the top view until it is closed and Modal has only one toplevel which can contain any of the documents at any one time, however only one can be displayed. If you have ever used Emacs Modal is very similar to the way Emacs handles buffers. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  MDI notebook tab position - If you choose to use the Notebook style you may then decide where you want the tabs to appear in your applications. You may have them at the top, left, right, or bottom of your application. Keep in mind that these choices will affect applications that are GNOME compliant. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1660}{\*\bkmkend _1660}\b\lang1024 Figure 9-16. MDI Capplet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gccmdi.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\sect\sectd\plain\pgwsxn12240\pghsxn15840\marglsxn1440\margrsxn1440\margtsxn1440\margbsxn1920\headery0\footery0\pgndec\titlepg{\headerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}{\headerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i Chapter 10. A Word About Session Management}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i \chpgn }\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\headerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i Chapter 10. A Word About Session Management}\par}{\footerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}\pard\sb373\s1\sl647 {\*\bkmkstart ID_SESSION}{\*\bkmkend ID_SESSION}\b\fs49\f1 Chapter 10. A Word About Session Management\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_SESSION_45_INTRO}{\*\bkmkend ID_SESSION_45_INTRO}\fs41 10.1. Introduction\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  You might have seen a little bit about session management when you read about GNOME. Session management can be a very useful tool for you in your use of GNOME and GNOME applications. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The main idea of session management is that your work will be saved whenever you log out of GNOME. Your GNOME "Session" is currently saved when you log out, however you may not notice all that it can do. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Probably one of the most useful features of session management is the ability to start applications you had open when you logged out of GNOME. This is easily demonstrated as you exit GNOME and enter again. You will see your applications re-appear in the same location on your desktop as they were when you logged out. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  If there are certain applications you wish to start up whenever you log in, even if they were not open the last time your session was saved, you may add them to the Session Manager Capplet which you can read about in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_GCCSESSION}{\fldrslt Section 9.7}}. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \b\fs22\lang1024\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 If you have heard about application data being session managed you have heard about the future of GNOME. For application data to be saved correctly you must be using a fully compliant GNOME application. At the time of publication of this manual there were not any applications that offer full session management for your data, so until there are some and you are aware of their capabilities you should not rely on session management to save your application data.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_RESET_45_SESSION}{\*\bkmkend ID_RESET_45_SESSION}\b\fs41 10.2. Resetting the GNOME Session\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  One advanced feature of the GNOME Session Manager is the ability to recover a "clean session" if anything goes wrong for you. To do this you must hold down the \b CTRL\b0  and \b SHIFT\b0  keys together when you log in to GNOME. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  This will bring up a dialog box which gives you two different options for restoring your GNOME Session. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The first option is to \f1 Start with default programs\f0 . This option will remove all of the session configuration setting in respect to applications. This will only erase the GNOME session data for applications you had running when you logged out last, it will not change any information you may have set in the Session Manager Capplet in the GNOME Control Center. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The second option is to \f1 Reset all user settings\f0 . This will reset all GNOME application, and core configuration data. This option will destroy any configurations you have made to the Panel, the GNOME File Manager, the Session Manager Capplet, and any GNOME application. This option will not remove files on your desktop. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \b\fs22\lang1024\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 These options are for advanced users and should only be used in case there is a problem with your GNOME Session. You can lose data for many applications if you utilize the functionality provided by these options.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1690}{\*\bkmkend _1690}\b\fs24\f0 Figure 10-1. Login Screen for Resetting GNOME Session\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/login.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\sect\sectd\plain\pgwsxn12240\pghsxn15840\marglsxn1440\margrsxn1440\margtsxn1440\margbsxn1920\headery0\footery0\pgndec\titlepg{\headerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}{\headerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i Chapter 11. Panel Applets}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i \chpgn }\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\headerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i Chapter 11. Panel Applets}\par}{\footerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}\pard\sb373\s1\sl647 {\*\bkmkstart ID_PANELAPPS}{\*\bkmkend ID_PANELAPPS}\b\fs49\f1 Chapter 11. Panel Applets\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart _1697}{\*\bkmkend _1697}\fs41 11.1. Introduction\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  {\*\bkmkstart ID_IDX_45_B2}{\*\bkmkend ID_IDX_45_B2}This section describes the GNOME applets that are available to add to the GNOME Panel. To access these applets right mouse click on the Panel and select \f1 Add new applet\f0  from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSAMUSE}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSAMUSE}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 11.2. Amusements\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The Amusement applets are designed to make your life more enriched by providing you with a complete waste of time and resources purely for your entertainment. If you find that valuable space in your brain has been filled with something an Amusement applet has taught you, then the authors of that applet have succeeded in their task. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSMON}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSMON}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 11.3. Monitors\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  Monitor Applets are designed to be used to keep track of your system and its functions. You can monitor the resources of your machine, which allows you to keep close tabs on how things are working. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSBATMON}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSBATMON}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 11.3.1. Battery Monitor\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The Battery Monitor is a simple applet that allows you to see how much time you have remaining on your laptop monitor. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSCHARGE}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSCHARGE}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 11.3.2. Battery Charge Monitor\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The Battery Charge Monitor indicates what percentage or your laptop's battery charge remains and how long the laptop can run with this charge. It also indicates if the laptop is currently plugged in. If you left click on the applet, the display will change to a graph plotting the remaining charge on the vertical axis and the time on the horizontal. So if your laptop has been charging, the graph should be rising and if it has been running on batteries, the graph should be falling. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Right clicking on the applet will bring up a pop-up menu. If you click on the Properties menu item you can edit properties such as which colors to use in the display, when to notify you of a low battery, and the general look of the applet. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSUSAGE}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSUSAGE}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 11.3.3. CPU/MEM Usage Monitor\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The CPU/MEM Usage Monitor is an applet that will show you the current usage of CPU, Memory, and Swap Space. The applet consists of three bars that are shaded with colors to represent the usage. If you are running the applet on a horizontal panel the top bar is CPU, the middle bar is Memory, and the bottom bar is Swap Space. If you are running the applet on a vertical panel the CPU is the left bar, Memory is the middle bar, and Swap Space is the right bar. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1739}{\*\bkmkend _1739}\b\lang1024 Figure 11-1. The CPU/MEM Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/cpumem-applet.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \b0\fs19 \'95\tab \fs24 CPU - The CPU bar will break down current CPU usage by means of three colors. The yellow shows the current hit by the current user. Grey shows the current hit by non-user specified system activity. Black show idle use. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  MEMORY - The Memory bar shows the current physical memory usage with one of four colors. The yellow show the current shared memory usage. The grey-yellow show other memory usage. The grey shows the buffers being used. The Green show free physical memory available on your system. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  SWAP SPACE - The Swap Space bar shows how much swap space is being used with a yellow bar. Any free swap space will be shown with a green bar. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSCPU}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSCPU}\b\fs34\f1 11.3.4. CPULoad Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The CPULoad Applet is a simple graph that shows you the current CPU Usage using three colors: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1757}{\*\bkmkend _1757}\b\lang1024 Figure 11-2. The CPULoad Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/CPULoad.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  The yellow shows the current hit by the current user. Grey shows the current hit by non-user specified system activity. Black show idle use. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSMEM}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSMEM}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 11.3.5. MEMLoad Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The MEMLoad is a simple graph that shows you the current Memory usage using four colors: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1769}{\*\bkmkend _1769}\b\lang1024 Figure 11-3. The MEMLoad Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/MEMLoad.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  The yellow show the current shared memory usage. The grey-yellow show other memory usage. The grey shows the buffers being used. The Green shows free physical memory available on your system. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSSWAP}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSSWAP}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 11.3.6. SWAPLoad Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The SWAPLoad is a simple graph that shows you the current Swap Space usage using two colors: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1781}{\*\bkmkend _1781}\b\lang1024 Figure 11-4. The SWAPLoad Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/SWAPLoad.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  The yellow bar shows how much swap space is currently being used. Any free swap space will be shown with a green bar. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSMM}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSMM}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 11.4. Multimedia\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The Multimedia Applets are a collection of applets that allow you to utilize multimedia on your system. You will find applets that control sound, video, and other multimedia. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSCD}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSCD}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 11.4.1. CD Player Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The CD Player Applet is a simple CD player that resides in the panel. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  When you have an audio CD in your CDROM drive you may use the Play/Pause, Stop, Forward, backward and Eject buttons to control your CD for playback. Above the buttons is a small display that shows the time remaining on the track and in between the Forward and Backward buttons is the track number. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1800}{\*\bkmkend _1800}\b\lang1024 Figure 11-5. The CD Player Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/cdapplet.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \fs22\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 You must have the correct access rights to your CDROM drive for this applet to be successful. Some systems, will normally grant you the necessary rights automatically when you log into the console. The mechanism that does this is called the pam_console. If your system doesn't give you the necessary rights to the CDROM, then you will need to be given those rights. If you have the root password type the following in a terminal window. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl257 \fs19\f2        $ su \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
       $ Password: [type  in root password] \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
       $ chmod a+r /dev/cdrom\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
       $ exit\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
      \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \fs22\f1 If your CDROM is located somewhere other than /dev/cdrom make sure you change it in the commands above.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \fs24\lang1033\f0  If you want more control over your CD you may right mouse click on the CD Player Applet and select \f1 Run gtcd\f0  from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. This will launch the GNOME CD Player which you can read more about in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_GTCD}{\fldrslt Chapter 12}}. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \b\fs22\lang1024\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 When the CD Player Applet is running you will not have physical control over the eject button on your CDROM drive. If you wish to eject the CD you must use the Eject Button on the CD Player Applet.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSMIX}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSMIX}\b\fs34 11.4.2. Mixer Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The Mixer Applet is a simple applet that allows you to control the volume on your system. There are two main controls on the applet: the Volume Slidebar and the Mute button. To raise or lower the volume use the slide bar with your mouse. To mute your system press the small mute button on the bottom of the applet. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1824}{\*\bkmkend _1824}\b\lang1024 Figure 11-6. The Mixer Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/mixapplet.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  If you want more control over your system volume you may right mouse click on the Mixer Applet and select the \f1 Run gmix\f0  menu item from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSNET}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSNET}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 11.5. Network\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  Network applets enable your work on a network or the internet to be monitored or enhanced. Network applets range from checking mail to monitoring the time you have spent on the internet. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSMAIL}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSMAIL}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 11.5.1. MailCheck Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The Mailcheck applet will check mail on your system and let you know if there is new mail waiting for you. At this point it will only check your local system mail. It will not query another server for your mail. To access the properties for the Mailcheck applet right mouse click on the applet and select the \f1 Properties\f0  menu item from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. The Mail check properties dialog box will appear and you may change the following properties. If you would like to execute a program before each update you may enter a command in the Execute text box. This can be useful if you want to run fetchmail to retrieve your mail from another server. You may also specify how often you check for mail and select which animation style you would like displayed in the applet. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSWEB}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSWEB}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 11.5.2. WebControl Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The WebControl applet allows you to launch your web browser with the URL you indicate in the URL text box. If you would like to launch a new window instead of using the active one you may check the Launch new window checkbox. To clear the URL textbox, press the \f1 Clear\f0  button. To access the properties, right mouse click on the WebControl applet and select the \f1 Properties\f0  menu item from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. The Web Control properties dialog box will appear and you can select whether you want to Display the URL text label and the launch new window options on your applet. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSMODEM}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSMODEM}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 11.5.3. Modem Lights Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The Modem Lights Applet is a handy applet that will start you dial up connection and monitor it for you once it is connected. It derives its name by displaying two small modem lights which monitor the activity on your modem. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Setting up modem lights requires you to already have a dial up connection working on your system. You must right mouse click on the applet and select the \f1 Properties\f0  menu item from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. This will launch the Modem Lights Setting dialog. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Within this dialog are two tabs, the \f1 General\f0  tab and the \f1 Advanced\f0  tab. In the \f1 General\f0  you type the scripts used to start your dialup connection in the \f1 Connect command\f0  textbox. The disconnect scripts are typed in the \f1 Disconnect command\f0  textbox. Press Apply and then press the small single button at the edge of the applet. The scripts will be run. Once there is a connection the small modem lights will blink and the internet load will be displayed in the small black box in the center of the applet. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSUTIL}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSUTIL}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 11.6. Utility\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The Utility Applets are a set of general utilities to use in your work environment. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSCLOCK}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSCLOCK}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 11.6.1. Clock Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The Clock applet is the one of the only applets that is loaded by default when you install GNOME for the first time. To access the clock properties, right mouse click on the clock and select the \f1 Properties\f0  menu item from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. The Clock Properties dialog box will appear allowing you to specify whether you would like 12 or 24 hour time to be displayed. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSPRINT}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSPRINT}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 11.6.2. Printer Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The Printer Applet is represented by a small printer icon that lives on your Panel. If you drag a file to the Printer Applet it will print the file for you. To set up the Printer Applet, right mouse click on it and select the \f1 Properties\f0  menu item from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. This will bring up the Printer properties dialog box. In this dialog you may specify a printer name and the Print Command. For most systems the Print Command will be \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl281 \fs21\f2 lpr\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \fs24\f0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1890}{\*\bkmkend _1890}\b\lang1024 Figure 11-7. The Printer Applet Properties\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/printer-applet-props.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSDRIVE}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSDRIVE}\fs34\f1 11.6.3. Drive Mount Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  On many Unix-like systems, after inserting a disk you must tell the computer to mount it in order to use that disk. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The Drive Mount Applet allows you or your systems administrator to mount a drive on your system by simply clicking the icon on your Panel. In order for this to work you will to have to set the drive you want to access to be user mountable. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  This can be done quite easily with someone with root permissions if they have \i linuxconf\i0  installed on your machine. Just select the drive you want to access in the \f1 Access local drive\f0  section. In the \f1 Options\f0  tab select the \f1 User Mountable\f0  option. This drive will now be mountable by all users. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  If you do not have \i linuxconf\i0  someone with root access must edit your \i /etc/fstab\i0  to include user access. This is done by adding user access to the drive specification. For Example: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  If your fstab file looks like this: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl281 \fs21\f2        /dev/cdrom /mnt/cdrom iso9660 exec,dev,ro,noauto 0 0\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
      \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \fs24\f0  Add "user" to the fourth column: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl281 \fs21\f2       /dev/cdrom /mnt/cdrom iso9660 user,exec,dev,ro,noauto 0 0\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
     \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \fs24\f0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Now that you can mount the drive without being root you may add the Drive Mount Applet to your panel by selecting \f1 Drive Mount\f0  from the \f1 Utilities\f0  menu in the \f1 Add new applet\f0  menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  You will see a small drive image on your Panel that looks like a floppy drive. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1920}{\*\bkmkend _1920}\b\lang1024 Figure 11-8. The Drive Mount Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/drive.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  The Drive Mount applet will always default to access your floppy drive. You may change this by right mouse clicking on the applet and selecting the \f1 Properties\f0  item from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1928}{\*\bkmkend _1928}\b\lang1024 Figure 11-9. The Drive Mount Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/drive-prefs.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  The \f1 Drive Mount Settings\f0  dialog allows you to define which drive you want to mount and where it is located. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The first option is how many seconds you wish to have between applet updates. During updates, the applet will check the drive status to see if it is mounted (in case it was mounted or unmounted by other means) and will display the applet accordingly. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The second option you have is which icon to be displayed. You have a choice of four icons, Floppy, CDROM, Zip Disk, and Hard Drive. After you have selected the icon you must put the correct mount point for the drive in the \f1 Mount point\f0  text box. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The last option to set in the \f1 Drive Mount Settings\f0  is whether or not you wish to \f1 Use automount friendly status test\f0  If you are using a system that utilizes autofs to auto-mount your drives the Drive Mount applet might interfere with autofs. If this is the case you should select this option. If you are not using autofs (which is most likely the case) do not select this option as it is taxing on your system and is much slower. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_APPLETSPAGER}{\*\bkmkend ID_APPLETSPAGER}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 11.6.4. GNOME Pager\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The GNOME Pager is an applet that will show you all of your virtual desktops and the applications within them. There are two main areas on the GNOME Pager, the desktops view and the applications view. In the desktop view each of your desktops will be represented as a small rectangle. If there are any applications on the desktops, they will show up as small outlines according to their position on the desktop. The Applications view will show you the applications on your active desktop in a list view. If you press the button in the middle that contains the arrow it will show you a view of all desktops and list the applications that are currently on them. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1953}{\*\bkmkend _1953}\b\lang1024 Figure 11-10. The GNOME Pager\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gnome-pager.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \fs22\f1 NOTE: \b0 If windows "disappear" from your screen when you iconify them, just add a GNOME Pager to your Panel.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \fs24\lang1033\f0  You may access the GNOME Pager Settings dialog with a right mouse click on the Pager and select the \f1 Properties\f0  menu item from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The GNOME Pager Settings dialog contains two tabs, the \f1 Pager\f0  and the \f1 Tasklist\f0  tabs. The \f1 Pager\f0  tab allows you to change the setting for the Pager (graphical representation of desktops) and the \f1 Tasklist\f0  tab allows you to change the settings of your Tasklist (list of open applications on your desktop). \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _1969}{\*\bkmkend _1969}\b\lang1024 Figure 11-11. The GNOME Pager Properties\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gnome-pager-props.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \b0\fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Pager\f0  - \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Show Pager\f0  - This allows you to show the pager or not. Not showing the Pager will allow you to just use the tasklist. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Place pagers after tasklist\f0  - This allows you to switch the location of the pager and the tasklist from left to right and top to bottom depending on the orientation of your Panel. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Width of small pagers\f0  - If you have the small pagers on you can define the width here. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Height of small pagers\f0  - If you have the small pagers on you can define the height here. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Width of large pagers\f0  - If you have the large pagers on you can define the width here. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Height of large pagers\f0  - If you have the large pagers on you can define the height here. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Tasklist\f0  - \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Show task list button\f0  - This toggles the tasklist button. The task list button is the small button with the up arrow which brings up a list of all tasks on all desktops when pressed. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Show task list\f0  - You can choose to show the task list or use the pager alone. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Show button icons\f0  - This will toggle icons on the task list buttons. Turning them off may save you some space. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Which tasks to show\f0  - this area lets you define which applications will show up in the task list and when. You can choose to have all tasks, normal tasks only, minimized tasks only, all tasks on all desktops, or all minimized tasks on all desktops. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1440\sl312\fi-240 \tx1440 \fs17 \'95\tab \fs24  \f1 Geometry\f0  - this area allows you to change the geometry of the tasklist. You can have the tasklist always display at minimum size or change the width of the horizontal and vertical task lists. You may also specify the number of rows of horizontal tasks and the number of vertical columns of tasks. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_QUICKLAUNCH}{\*\bkmkend ID_QUICKLAUNCH}\b\fs34\f1 11.6.5. Quicklaunch Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The Quicklaunch Applet is a small applet that gives you a repository to place launchers. The Quicklaunch applet holds the application launchers you wish to have and allows you to click on them to launch the applications. Drag and drop functionality makes the set up of the Quicklaunch applet very easy and quick. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _2023}{\*\bkmkend _2023}\b\lang1024 Figure 11-12. The Quicklaunch Applet\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/quicklaunch.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  To add a launcher to the Quicklaunch applet you must already have the launcher set up either in the Main Menu, on your Panel, or on your desktop. Once you have the launcher you may drag it onto the Quicklaunch applet to create a small launcher button. To launch the application simply press the launcher button. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  To drag a launcher from your Main Menu click once on the Main Menu to open it, and click once on the sub menu to open it. Now move the mouse to the application desired, press (but do not release) the left mouse button, drag the application to the Quicklaunch applet and release the button. To drag a launcher from either the Panel or your desktop, move the mouse to the launcher, press and hold the left mouse button, drag the application to the Quicklaunch applet, and release the button. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Once the launcher is in the Quicklaunch applet you may right mouse click on it and select \f1 Properties\f0  to change any properties associated with the launcher. The dialog that is launched is the standard GNOME launcher properties dialog, which you can read more about in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_PANELAPPLAUNCH}{\fldrslt Section 4.4.1}}. \hyphpar0\par\sect\sectd\plain\pgwsxn12240\pghsxn15840\marglsxn1440\margrsxn1440\margtsxn1440\margbsxn1920\headery0\footery0\pgndec\titlepg{\headerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}{\headerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i Chapter 12. GNOME CD Player}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i \chpgn }\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\headerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i Chapter 12. GNOME CD Player}\par}{\footerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}\pard\sb373\s1\sl647 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GTCD}{\*\bkmkend ID_GTCD}\b\fs49\f1 Chapter 12. GNOME CD Player\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart _2035}{\*\bkmkend _2035}\fs41 12.1. Introduction\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The GNOME CD Player (gtcd) is a GNOME enabled application that is preloaded with GNOME. This is a simple CD Player which allows you to listen to Compact Discs on your PC. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GTCD_45_USE}{\*\bkmkend ID_GTCD_45_USE}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 12.2. Using the GNOME CD Player\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The GNOME CD Player will be available to you in the Main Menu in the Audio menu and can also be invoked in the command line with \b $gtcd\b0 . \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _2044}{\*\bkmkend _2044}\b\lang1024 Figure 12-1. The GNOME CD Player\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gtcd.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \fs22\f1 IMPORTANT: \b0 You must have the correct access rights to your CDROM drive for this application to be successful. Some systems, will normally grant you the necessary rights automatically when you log into the console. The mechanism that does this is called the pam_console. If your system doesn't give you the necessary rights to the CDROM, then you will need to be given those rights. If you have the root password type the following in a terminal window. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl257 \fs19\f2       $ su \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
      $ Password: [type  in root password] \sa0\par\fi0\sb0
      $ chmod a+r /dev/cdrom\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
      $ exit\sa0\par\fi0\sb0
     \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \fs22\f1 If your CDROM is located somewhere other than /dev/cdrom make sure you change it in the commands above.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \fs24\lang1033\f0  The GNOME CD Player works like any CD Player with common buttons such as Play, Stop, Pause, etc. Plus a track selector button that displays the track titles in a drop down menu. You have access to change various properties by pressing the \f1 Preferences\f0  button. This will bring up the GNOME CD Player Preferences dialog. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  There are three tabs in the GNOME CD Player Preferences dialog: Preferences, Keybindings, and CDDB Settings. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _2058}{\*\bkmkend _2058}\b\lang1024 Figure 12-2. The GNOME CD Player Properties\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/gtcd-props.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \b0\fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Preferences Tab - In this dialog you may specify: \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312 \lang1033  What you would like the GNOME CD Player to do when first started, and when exited. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312  The location of your CDROM on your system. This is usually \b /dev/cdrom\b0 . \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312  The Color to display the Track and CD Title. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312  The Font to display the Track and CD Title. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312  Whether you would like handles on the title window which will allow you to drag the title window off of the CD Player to float on the desktop. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312  Whether tooltips are enabled when your mouse is over the buttons. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19\lang1024 \'95\tab \fs24  Keybindings Tab - In this tab you can change the key bindings associated with the GNOME CD Player. These keybindings allow you to use the Player without using your mouse. If you want to change one of the bindings, select it with your mouse and type the new key in the \b Click here to change\b0  text box. Press Apply to save the changes \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  CDDB Settings Tab - CDDB stands for CD Database and is a huge global database of CD information. Each CD has an identity, which the CD Player can read. If you are connected to the internet, it will then search a CDDB server for that CD identity and return any information it has on it. This usually includes CD Title, Artist, and track titles. It can also include notes and lyric information. Once this data is retrieved, the GNOME CD Player will store the information on your hard drive for future access. In the CDDB Setting tab you can change the CDDB server and edit your local CDDB database. You can read more about CDDB by visiting the CDDB Website (http://www.cddb.org). \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312 \lang1033  Another feature in the GNOME CD Player is the Track Editor. The track editor can be launched by the \f1 Track Editor\f0  button on the main GNOME CD Player window. The Track Editor allows you to edit the CD track information in case it is incorrect or there was no CDDB entry for your CD. You may also check the status of the CDDB information by pressing the \f1 CDDB Status\f0  button at the bottom of the Track Editor. This will show you what messages, if any, were returned from the CDDB server. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _2082}{\*\bkmkend _2082}\b\lang1024 Figure 12-3. The GNOME CD Player Track Editor\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/trackeditor.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\sect\sectd\plain\pgwsxn12240\pghsxn15840\marglsxn1440\margrsxn1440\margtsxn1440\margbsxn1920\headery0\footery0\pgndec\titlepg{\headerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}{\headerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i Chapter 13. The GNOME Calendar}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i \chpgn }\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\headerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i Chapter 13. The GNOME Calendar}\par}{\footerr\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}\pard\sb373\s1\sl647 {\*\bkmkstart ID_GCAL}{\*\bkmkend ID_GCAL}\b\fs49\f1 Chapter 13. The GNOME Calendar\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart _2089}{\*\bkmkend _2089}\fs41 13.1. Introduction\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The GNOME Calendar is a simple calendar application which can be quite useful in your daily work. The Calendar, like much of GNOME, is in its infancy and while it is a very useful application, there is some very impressive functionality still to come like network shared calendar usage, and syncing capability with Palm Pilots and other hand held PDAs. The Calendar can be launched from the \f1 Applications\f0  submenu of the Main Menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The Calendar is broken up into four main tabs: Day, Week, Month, and Year. Each view allows you to view the respective time period but will also allow you to schedule appointments from any one of the tabs. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _2098}{\*\bkmkend _2098}\b\lang1024 Figure 13-1. The GNOME Calendar\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/calday.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_CALSETUP}{\*\bkmkend ID_CALSETUP}\fs41\f1 13.2. Setting Up the GNOME Calendar\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The GNOME Calendar can be used in the state which it is shipped but there are tools available to make sure it is setup the way you would like it to be. The first place you should go is the GNOME Calendar Preferences. You can find the Preferences dialog by selecting the \f1 Preferences\f0  menu item from the \f1 Settings\f0  menu. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _2108}{\*\bkmkend _2108}\b Figure 13-2. The GNOME Calendar Preferences\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/cal-props.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  The Calendar Preferences dialog is broken up into three tabs, Time display, Colors, and Todo List \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Time - This tab is broken up into three main sections: Time format, Weeks start on, and Day range. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Time format - This allows you to choose between a 12 or 24 hour format clock. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Weeks start on - This allows you to define what day your week will start on, Sunday or Monday. This will affect how the calendar is laid out in the Day and Week views. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Day range - This section lets you choose what time your days will start and end. Any hours outside the range selected will be shaded on your Day view. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Colors - This tab allows you to change the default colors used in the Calendar. There are seven color choices you can customize: Outline, Headings, Empty days, Appointments, Highlighted day, Day numbers, and Current day's number. Each choice has a small color selector box next to it. When you press this box you will be given a color selector dialog in which you can choose the color you want. Once you have selected a color the small sample calendar on the right side of the tab will preview your choice. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Todo List - This tab allows you to define which columns will be shown in the Todo List in the Day View. You can set the Summary, Due Date, and Priority columns. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Once you have made the changes to the Calendar Preferences you may press the \f1 Apply\f0  button to apply them. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_CALUSE}{\*\bkmkend ID_CALUSE}\b\fs41\lang1024\f1 13.3. Using the GNOME Calendar\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  Using the GNOME Calendar is quite simple and most tasks can be performed from any of the major views, Day, Week, Month or Year. Probably one of the most important features to remember is that at any time you may right mouse click on a particular day and add a new appointment. There are many other features which will be described below in each of the major views. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_CALDAY}{\*\bkmkend ID_CALDAY}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 13.3.1. The Day View\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The Day tab is probably the most useful view in the GNOME Calendar as it acts just as a day timer would. On the left of the tab is the hour listing for the current day. The light grey coloring in the hour list separates the work hours from the non-work hours. If you would like to change the work hours displayed in light grey you can do so in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_CALSETUP}{\fldrslt Section 13.2}}. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _2129}{\*\bkmkend _2129}\b\lang1024 Figure 13-3. The Day View\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/calday.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li1440\sl286 \fs22\f1 TIP: \b0 One tip for adding a new appointment in the Day View is to select a few hours in the hours list by clicking and dragging your mouse down the hours list. Once the correct range of time has been selected you may press Enter and type in the appointment. This will allow you to skip the Create New Appointment dialog.\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \fs24\lang1033\f0  Next to the hours listing in the top right hand corner is a small full month calendar. You may change the month or year of the small month calendar by pressing the forward and backward arrows on the top. You may use the small month calendar to navigate the days as well. Double clicking on any day in the small month calendar will move the current day view to that particular day. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Below the small month calendar is your Todo list. The Todo list is a simple list where you can keep all your tasks on hand. To add an item to the Todo list press the \f1 Add\f0  button. This will launch a small editing box where you can type in the item. Once you have entered an item in the To-do list you may use the \f1 Edit\f0  and \f1 Delete\f0  to manage you items. The To-do items are available no matter which days are displayed in the Day View and can only be deleted with the \f1 Delete\f0  button. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_CALWEEK}{\*\bkmkend ID_CALWEEK}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 13.3.2. The Week View\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The Week View shows the current week with detailed descriptions of your appointments. If you would like to add an appointment for any of the days in the week view, you may right mouse click on the day and select the \f1 New appointment\f0  menu item from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. You may also use the week view to navigate to particular days in the Day View. Double-click on any day in the Week View and you will go to that day in the Day View. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _2148}{\*\bkmkend _2148}\b\lang1024 Figure 13-4. The Week View\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/calweek.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 \b0\lang1033  In the lower left corner of the Week View there is a small month calendar. You may change the month or year of the small month calendar by pressing the forward and backward arrows on the top. You may use the small month calendar to navigate the days as well. Double clicking on any day in the small month calendar will move the current week view to that particular week. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_CALMONTH}{\*\bkmkend ID_CALMONTH}\b\fs34\lang1024\f1 13.3.3. The Month View\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The Month View shows the entire month with brief detailed descriptions of your appointments. The Month View makes use of the customized colors available in the Calendar. You may read about how to set these colors in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_CALSETUP}{\fldrslt Section 13.2}}. For any day with a brief description of an appointment you may click on the day to display a detailed description of the appointment in a pop-up window. If you would like to add an appointment to a day in the Month View you may right mouse click on any day and select the \f1 New Appointment in this day\f0  item from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. You may use the items in the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu to navigate in the Day, Week, and Year views by selecting either \f1 Jump to this day\f0 , \f1 Jump to this week\f0 , or \f1 Jump to this Year\f0 . \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _2164}{\*\bkmkend _2164}\b\lang1024 Figure 13-5. The Month View\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/calmonth.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb259\s3\sl449 {\*\bkmkstart ID_CALYEAR}{\*\bkmkend ID_CALYEAR}\fs34\f1 13.3.4. The Year View\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb173\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  The Year View shows you the entire year with no descriptions of appointments. Like the Month View, the Year View makes use of the customized colors available in the Calendar. You may read about how to set these colors in {\field{\*\fldinst   HYPERLINK  \\l ID_CALSETUP}{\fldrslt Section 13.2}}. If you have an appointment on a day you may click on that day and a description of the appointment will be displayed in the pop-up window. If you would like to add an appointment to a day in the Year View you may right mouse click on any day and select the \f1 New Appointment in this day\f0  item from the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu. You may use the items in the \f1 pop-up\f0  menu to navigate in the Day, Week, and Month views by selecting either \f1 Jump to this day\f0 , \f1 Jump to this week\f0 , or \f1 Jump to this Month\f0 . \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960\sl312 {\*\bkmkstart _2179}{\*\bkmkend _2179}\b\lang1024 Figure 13-6. The Year View\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb240\li960{\field\flddirty{\*\fldinst INCLUDEPICTURE "./figs/calyear.eps" }{\fldrslt }}\par\pard\sb311\s2\sl539 {\*\bkmkstart ID_CALAPPOINT}{\*\bkmkend ID_CALAPPOINT}\fs41\f1 13.4. Making a New Appointment\keepn\hyphpar0\par\pard\sb207\li960\sl312 \b0\fs24\lang1033\f0  There are many methods for making a new appointment in the GNOME Calendar, the easiest is by pressing the \f1 New\f0  button on the button bar. Whenever you make a new appointment you will launch the Create New Appointment dialog that allows you to set the properties of that appointment. The Create New Appointment dialog is broken into two different tabs, the General and the Recurrence tabs. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  General - The General tab is the area in which you specify the time of the appointment and set reminders for yourself. There are four different areas on the General tab: Summary, Time, Alarms, and Classification. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Summary - The Summary box allows you to type a description of the appointment. Keep in mind that only a portion of this description will be available in the Week and Month Views. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Time - The Time area allows you to set the time range for the appointment by selecting the date and hours. To the right of the start and end days there is a small selection box named Calendar. This will bring up a small Calendar when pressed. You may select the start and end date in the small calendar. To the right of the start and end hours there is a small button that will display the hours of the day when pressed. Each hour in the list will have a sub menu displaying each quarter hour so you may select them. The hours are restricted to those included in the Day Range. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li1200\sl312\fi-240 \tx1200 \fs19 \'95\tab \fs24  Alarms - The Alarms area allows you to set up an alarm to remind you of an appointment. There are four different types of alarms you may use to remind yourself of appointments: Display, Audio, Program, and Mail. The Display alarm will display a message on your screen at the time you set. The Audio alarm will play an audio file at the time you set. The Program alarm will run a program you specify at the time you set. The Mail alarm will send email to the user specified at the time you set. \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  \hyphpar0\par\pard\sb120\li960\sl312  Recurrence - The Recurrence tab allows you to specify how often an appointment should recur, if at all. The first property you should set if you want a recurring appointment is the Recurrence rule. You may choose among None, Daily, Weekly, Monthly, and Yearly. For each selection you may adjust the recurrence properties for your selection. In the Ending date area you may set a rule which will stop the recurrence of your appointment or allow it to repeat forever. In the Exceptions area you may make exceptions to the recurring appointment by double clicking the date and pressing the \f1 Add\f0  button. \hyphpar0\par\sect\sectd\plain\pgwsxn12240\pghsxn15840\marglsxn1440\margrsxn1440\margtsxn1440\margbsxn1920\headery0\footery0\pgndec\titlepg{\headerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {}\par}{\footerf\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa910\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {}\tab {}\tab {\i \chpgn }\par}{\headerl\pard\sl-240\sb770\sa430\plain\tqc\tx4680\tqr\tx9360 {\i Chapter 14. GNOME User's Guide Documentation Team}\tab {}\tab {}\par}